{Welcome to the second part of the Anti-Sicilian database! We will continue to
avoid the main lines of the Sicilian and delve into popular sidelines. I will
try to stay true to the original spirit of the first part and offer you
variations which are easy to remember and play on the board. After all, that
is the whole concept of the Anti Sicilian approach!} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{Similarly like in the first part of the Anti Najdorf database, also here I
recommend developing the bishop first and delaying d2-d4 for the time being -
this is the Rossolimo variation which in my eyes is the only reasonable
alternative instead of the main lines. There are several ideas White would
want to employ in this setup so that you will have a better understanding of
what's going on here. Remember, it's more important to understand key ideas of
any position, rather than remembering the moves in an exact order. 1) In
several occasions White wants to take on c6, thus creating doubled pawns in
the Black's camp and a potential target in the future. However, it depends
which setup Black chooses - for example if Black continues with 3...g6 
(Chapters 8 and 9), I will explain to you why your best chance for success is
to do the exchange immediately. Then there's the tricky 3...e6 (Chapters 6 and
7) where I don't recommend taking the knight. 2) The fact that White has just
played Bb5 doesn't mean he will take on c6 automatically! At some occasions
White might retreat with the bishop, thus forcing Black to make some
weaknesses, or play the immediately d2-d4 breakthrough which sort of
contradicts with the whole Bb5 philosophy. But we will talk about that later.
3) If Black is too slow, White can think about grabbing the center with c2-c3
and d2-d4, thus getting a firm control of the center. In the first four
chapters I will cover most of the sidelines and starting from Chapter 5 head
to the main continuations.} a6 $6 {By this dubious move Black forces White to
take on c6 - however, for White this is a perfect moment to do it! White has
nothing better to do anyway.} (3... b6 $6 4. O-O $1 {while it was very
tempting to take on c6 (b7-b6 appears to be a useless move, and Black wouldn't
put the bishop on b7 after the trade anyway), it doesn't weaken the b6 square
as in 3...a6. So let's better continue development.} Bb7 5. Re1 e6 (5... a6 {
now, if Black insists, we can take on c6 and proceed with a direct assault in
the center.} 6. Bxc6 Bxc6 (6... dxc6 7. d3) 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 $14 {Black is
too much behind in development to hope for a good position.}) 6. c3 {[%cal
Gd2d4]} Nf6 (6... a6 7. Bf1 {One of those occasions when White is not obliged
to take on c6 and keeps the bishop. Probably also taking on c6 was good.} g5 $6
8. d4 $1 g4 9. Nfd2 cxd4 10. Qxg4 {1-0 (27) Gavrikov,V (2470)-Gurgenidze,B 
(2495) Tbilisi (Georgia) 1983} (10. cxd4 Nxd4 11. Nc4 $16)) 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4
a6 9. Bf1 d5 10. e5 Ne4 11. Nbd2 Nxd2 12. Bxd2 Be7 13. Bd3 $14 {[%cal Ga1c1,
Gd1e2,Ge2e3,Gh2h4] looks like a great version of French for White. The black
bishop is misplaced at b7, and White should organize an assault at the
kingside.}) (3... d5 $6 4. Nc3 $5 {I like this move more than} (4. exd5 Qxd5 5.
Nc3 Qe6+ 6. Be2 Nd4 {and White is still better, but his advantage needs to be
proved with precise moves. With my suggested move everything is much easier.})
4... d4 {Black has several moves at his disposal, none of them gives Black a
good game.} (4... e6 5. exd5 $1 exd5 6. O-O {[%csl Re8]} Be7 7. d4 Nf6 8. Ne5
Bd7 9. Nxd7 Qxd7 10. dxc5 O-O 11. Be3 $16) (4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 e6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6
7. O-O $14 {[%csl Rc5,Rc6]}) (4... Nf6 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. O-O Nxc3 7. dxc3 $5 Qxd1
8. Rxd1 f6 9. Be3 e5 10. Nd2 Bf5 11. Nb3 $1 $14) 5. Na4 e6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. O-O
$14 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gc2c3,Gd1c2]}) (3... Nd4 $6 {Similarly like in the Bird
variation of the Ruy Lopez variation, this early knight jump doesn't give
Black equality. The whole concept of the knight jump would make more sense if
White had already played Nc3, and thus after taking on d4 he would be obliged
to retreat with it.} 4. Nxd4 cxd4 5. c3 $1 {[%cal Re7e6,Rf8c5,Rg8e7,Re7c6] I
think this is more precise than castling immediately - the point is that Black
is unable to carry out his standard plan by keeping the control of the d4
square. If White would've castled here, Black could continue with e7-e6, Bc5
and possibly also Ne7-c6, aided with a potential Qb6. After the text move Bc5
now is impossible.} a6 (5... Nf6 {a nice attempt to trick White but it
shouldn't give Black the desired results.} 6. e5 Nd5 7. O-O $1 $14 {the d4
pawn isn't going anywhere! Now Black has to either give it up and quickly
finish development, or take on c3 and pray that everything will be alright.} (
7. cxd4 {is less clear} Qb6 8. Qa4 a6 9. Be2 Nf4 $132)) (5... dxc3 {the
circumstances may differ but normally White wants to take on c3 with the
knight, proceeding with d2-d4. However, if Black has played already e7-e6,
then dxc3 might be an interesting option to target the weakness on d6 by swift
action on the d-file.} 6. Nxc3) 6. Ba4 b5 7. Bc2 $1 {defending the e4 pawn in
advance against Bb7 - you will want to play d2-d4 in one attempt.} Qb6 $6 {
we've always known that the queen is a bad blockade.} (7... dxc3 8. Nxc3 $14 {
[%cal Gd2d4]}) (7... e5 8. cxd4 exd4 9. Bb3 d6 10. d3 Nf6 11. O-O $14) 8. O-O
e6 9. cxd4 $1 Qxd4 10. d3 Bb7 11. Nc3 Rc8 12. Be3 Qb4 13. Bb3 Ne7 14. d4 $16 {
[%cal Gd4d5] 1-0 (23) Palac,M (2543)-Colpa,H (2129) Omis 2004}) (3... Na5 $6 {
too eccentric for my taste but there are people who have played this! Pretty
much any plan will give White a stable advantage. My advice for players who
would play this as Black - play 2...Nc6 if you're concerned about the
Rossolimo!} 4. c3 {probably the simplest approach - any Alapin typical
structures will be in White's favour.} a6 5. Be2 Nf6 6. e5 Nd5 7. d4 cxd4 8.
O-O e6 (8... Nc6 9. cxd4 e6 10. Nc3 $14) 9. c4 $1 Ne7 10. Qxd4 Nac6 11. Qc3 $14
) (3... d6 {this move won't be covered in this database as it is already
analyzed in detail in the first part of the Anti Sicilian database, first
three chapters, just with a different order of the moves (1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.
Bb5 d6)}) 4. Bxc6 bxc6 {probably the most logical approach - the general rule
in chess is that pawns usually should be traded towards the center. However,
there are always exceptions. Here Black intends to use the two bishop
advantage and fight for the pawn center, however with precise play White will
always emerge superior.} (4... dxc6 {this setup would be good for Black if he
could manage to block the center with e7-e5. However, if White recognizes the
idea, he gets a solid advantage in every line.} 5. d3 Qc7 {[%cal Re7e5,Rf8d6,
Rg8e7]} 6. e5 $1 {a nice way to disrupt Black's plans!} Bg4 7. Nbd2 e6 (7... f5
$5 8. h3 Bh5 (8... Bxf3 9. Nxf3 e6 10. Be3 $14 {[%cal Gd1e2,Ge1c1]}) 9. Qe2 e6
10. g4 $36 {[%cal Gf3g5,Gd2c4,Gc4d6]}) 8. h3 Bh5 9. O-O Ne7 10. Re1 Nd5 {
½-½ (10) Campora,D (2506)-Arizmendi Martinez,J (2516) Lanzarote 2003. Here
the two GMs prematurely decided to call it quits - I think Black's position is
rather unpleasant with no clear game plan.} 11. Ne4 Be7 (11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3
Qxe5 13. Bg5 Qc7 14. c4 Nb4 15. Re2 {[%csl Rb4]} a5 16. a3 Na6 17. Bf4 Qd7 18.
Be5 $40) 12. c4 Nb6 13. Bf4 O-O 14. Qe2 Nd7 15. g4 Bg6 16. Ng3 $14 {[%cal
Gh3h5]}) 5. O-O d6 {[%cal Re7e5]} (5... d5 {[%csl Rc5] a direct approach to
grab the center gives Black nothing but trouble - the pawn on c5 becomes
eternally weak.} 6. d3 e6 (6... f6 {[%cal Re7e5] I will illustrate to you what
happens if Black insists on fighting for a strong pawn center and thus
neglecting the piece development.} 7. Nc3 e5 8. Nh4 $1 Ne7 9. f4 exf4 10. Bxf4
g5 11. Qh5+ Kd7 12. Bd2 gxh4 13. Rxf6 $18 {there is no safe haven for the
Black king, the attack is too powerful.}) 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 Be7 10.
e5 Nd7 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Na4 $14 {[%cal Gc2c4] Black is suffering here.}) 6. e5
$1 {White's plan in all of the lines is pretty much the same - target the weak
c5 pawn.} d5 {[%csl Rc5]} (6... Bg4 7. h3 Bh5 8. d3 $1 e6 9. Nc3 d5 (9... dxe5
10. g4 Bg6 11. Nxe5 Bd6 12. Qe2 $14) 10. Na4) (6... f6 $5 7. exd6 e5 8. d3 Bxd6
9. Nfd2 $1 {perhaps not mandatory but it does remove Black the option to make
a pin on g4.} Ne7 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Nce4 $14 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gd2b3,Gc1e3] If
Black understands what's going here, he will probably give away the c5 pawn
and seek counterplay at the kingside. However, in this scenario he has yet to
prove that the compensation is sufficient.}) 7. h3 Bf5 8. d3 {[%cal Gb1c3,
Gc3a4,Gc1e3]} e6 9. Nc3 h6 10. Na4 g5 11. g4 $1 {Stopping any counterplay at
the kingside, really classy! The weakened position of the white king doesn't
play any role here as Black can't exploit it.} (11. Be3 d4 12. Bd2 $14) 11...
Bg6 12. b3 $14 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc1a3,Gg1g2] White can gradually improve his
position and go for the c5 pawn while for Black it's tough to suggest anything
good.} *

