1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e5 {this relatively rare move leads to a position
which has a greater resemblance to the Ruy Lopez structures, rather than
Sicilian. Indeed, similarly like in the Ruy Lopez, also here White can't win
the e5 pawn by force. However, the inclusion of the c7-c5 push for the
particular structure is questionable - although it helps Black to fight for
the center and the d5 square weakness is meaningless, White is too far ahead
in development, and proceeds with the d2-d4 breakthrough anyway. Thus the
whole concept for Black is somewhat dubious, and perhaps can be used as a
surprise.} 4. O-O {now the threat to win the e5 pawn becomes very real.} (4.
Bxc6 $6 dxc6 5. Nxe5 $6 Qd4 $15 {[%cal Rd4e4,Rd4e5]}) 4... Bd6 {[%cal Rg8e7,
Re8g8,Rd6c7,Rd7d5] a very original approach to finish the development - Black
wants to play Nge7, 0-0, Bc7 and see what happens, most likely go for a d7-d5
push. Thus in White's best interest is to go for a quick breakthrough in the
center to exploit the awkward positioning of the black bishop.} (4... d6 $6 {
I don't think Black can afford to be so slow in the opening.} 5. c3 Bd7 (5...
Nf6 6. d4 {quite inevitably transforms to one of the lines covered later.} Nxe4
$4 7. d5 a6 8. Bd3 $18) 6. d4 Qc7 {It's obvious that White has an advantage in
development here but how to proceed? I suggest to treat it as King's Indian -
close the center first, and then transfer the weight of the position to the
queenside, by eventually opening the position with b2-b4.} (6... Nf6 $6 {
as it will become apparent very quickly, this logical move is not a good one.}
7. dxc5 $1 dxc5 8. Nbd2 Qc7 9. Nc4 {[%cal Gb5c6,Gf3e5]} Be7 10. Bxc6 Bxc6 11.
Nfxe5 Bxe4 (11... Nxe4 $4 12. Nxc6 Qxc6 13. Ne5 $18 {[%cal Gd1a4,Gd1d7]}) 12.
Bf4 Qd8 13. Qa4+ $16) (6... cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 8. Nxd4 $14 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gc1f4]
is just too easy for White - Black has no compensation for the weak pawn on d6
which will become a prime target very quickly.}) 7. d5 {[%cal Ga2a4,Gb1d2,
Gd2c4] White's plan here is straightforward - keep the c4 square for a knight
and by a2-a4-a5 secure a space advantage, followed by a b2-b4 break.} Nce7 8.
a4 Nf6 (8... a6 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Nbd2 Nf6 11. Nc4 Nc8 12. Re1 Be7 13. b4 cxb4
14. cxb4 $16) 9. Nbd2 g6 (9... Ng6 10. Re1 Be7 11. Nc4 O-O 12. Bxd7 Qxd7 13. a5
h6 14. Bd2 Nh7 15. Ne3 {[%cal Gb2b4]}) 10. Nc4 $1 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gd5d6]} Nc8 (
10... Nxe4 $4 11. Nfxe5 dxe5 12. d6 Qc8 13. dxe7 Bxe7 14. Qd5 $18) 11. Bxd7+
Qxd7 12. Re1 Bg7 (12... Nb6 13. Nfd2 Nxc4 14. Nxc4 Bg7 15. f4 $16) 13. a5 {
[%csl Rc8][%cal Rc8b6]} (13. b4 {also is good but it allows for Black to play
Nb6}) 13... O-O 14. b4 (14. Qa4 $2 Qxa4 15. Rxa4 b5 16. axb6 Nxb6 17. Nxb6 axb6
18. Rxa8 Rxa8 $15) 14... cxb4 (14... b5 15. axb6 Nxb6 16. Na5 cxb4 17. cxb4 $16
{[%csl Gc6]}) 15. cxb4 Ne8 16. Qb3 Nc7 17. Be3 f5 18. Rad1 $16) (4... Nge7 {
[%cal Rg7g6,Rf8g7,Re8g8,Rd7d5] Here Black intends to fianchetto the bishop on
g7, following by a castle and a breakthrough in the center. Like in most of
the lines of this chapter, also here a swift action in the center is
recommended before Black is ready. However, there are some nuances!} 5. c3 g6 (
5... a6 6. Ba4 b5 7. Bc2 {for Black this looks like a bad version of the Ruy
Lopez - clearly the knight on e7 is misplaced. It should have been on f6.} g6 (
7... d6 8. a4 b4 9. d4 $14) 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 exd4 10. Nxd4 (10. a4 $5) 10...
Bg7 11. Nxc6 Nxc6 12. Bb3 O-O 13. Nc3 $14) 6. d4 {now Black has to take on d4
twice - the order of the moves doesn't matter, right?} (6. Bxc6 $5 Nxc6 7. d4
d6 $1 {and Black is okay.}) (6. Nxe5 $6 $146 {for the blitz fanatics who seek
fresh and new positions!} Nxe5 7. d4 N5c6 8. d5 Nb8 9. Bg5 {and so on}) 6...
exd4 (6... cxd4 $6 {This order of the moves allows a powerful novelty.} 7. Bxc6
$5 $146 {and suddenly Black has solved some real problems.} Nxc6 (7... dxc6 8.
Nxe5 {and Black is already forced to sacrifice a pawn to keep the game going.})
8. cxd4 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gc3d5,Gc1g5] You might ask - why not play 6.Bxc6 Nxc6 7.
d4 immediately, reaching the same position? It's not the same - here Black has
already exchanged the c-pawns which favors White, allowing to execute a quick
Nc3-d5.} d6 (8... exd4 9. Nxd4 Bg7 10. Nb5 $14 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gb1c3,Gc1f4]})
9. Bg5 Be7 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Nc3 O-O 12. h3 $14 {with a very unpleasant
position for Black}) 7. cxd4 cxd4 8. Bf4 $1 {[%cal Gf4d6] in my opinion this
is a much stronger and energetic continuation than capturing back the pawn.
The white bishop goes to d6, binding all Black's pieces. The black pawn on d4
is entirely irrelevant - all that matters is the initiative.} (8. Nxd4 Bg7 9.
Be3 O-O 10. Nc3 {The main reason why I don't want to suggest this variation
for White is that Black can go for an immediate d7-d5 breakthrough; otherwise
this would be a simple and great line.} d5 11. exd5 Nb4 {anything else is just
outright bad for Black.} (11... Nxd5 $6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Nxd5 cxb5 (13... Qxd5
14. Qxd5 cxd5 15. Bc6 $16) 14. Bc5 Re8 15. Be7 $1 Qd7 (15... Rxe7 16. Nf6+ $18)
16. Re1 Kh8 17. Nf6 $16 {1-0 (45) Lazic,M (2539)-Andonov,B (2334) Cutro 2008})
12. Bg5 h6 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Re1 Qd6 15. Nde2 $14 {I have a feeling that the
pawn on d5 isn't going to hold for long. Black is very active and has
compensation for the sacrificed pawn.}) 8... Bg7 {yes, the bishop on d6 will
make Black feel uncomfortable, but what else?} (8... d6 $4 9. Qxd4 $18) (8...
a6 9. Bxc6 {probably also retreating with the bishop to either c4 or a4 is
equally good.} Nxc6 (9... dxc6 10. Be5 Rg8 11. Nxd4 $14 (11. Ng5 $5 h6 (11...
Bg7 12. Qb3 $1) 12. Nh7 $1 $36)) 10. Re1 $1 {[%cal Gf4d6,Gf4h6,Rf8e7,Rf8g7]
with an easy game for White. It is difficult to suggest anything good for
Black.}) 9. Bd6 {[%cal Gb1d2,Ga2a4,Gd1b3]} a6 (9... Qb6 10. Na3 {and White's
initiative is spreading itself - the pawn on d4 plays no role in this game,
neither does the b2 pawn.}) 10. Bd3 $1 O-O 11. Nbd2 {with a clear gameplan to
gain some space at the queenside. It is also possible that at the right moment
White might play e4-e5 and Nd2-e4; however, it enables Black the defensive
resource Ne7-f5, attacking the bishop. White has to be ready that Black wants
to drive it out by means of either Nc6-a5-b7 or Bb7 and Nc8. Here's a possible
illustration of what might happen next.} b6 (11... Re8 12. Qb3 b5 13. a4 Na5
14. Qc2 Nec6 15. axb5 Nb7 16. Ba3 {1-0 (22) Vachier Lagrave,M (2525) -Huertas,
G (1958) France 2005}) (11... b5 $6 {weakens too many squares at the queenside}
12. a4) 12. a4 Bb7 13. Qb3 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gd2c4]} Na5 14. Qa2 Bc6 15. b4 Nb7
16. Bg3 {[%cal Gd2b3,Gb3d4]} d5 17. e5 $1 {[%csl Rb7,Rc6,Rg7]} a5 18. b5 Nc5
19. Qa3 Bd7 20. Nxd4 $14 {and Black's troubles are far from over, White gains
a nice outpost at d4.}) (4... Nf6 $2 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nxe5 Nxe4 $4 7. Re1 Qd4 8.
Nf3 Qxf2+ 9. Kh1 Bf5 10. Nc3 $18) 5. c3 Nge7 6. d4 cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 8. Nxd4
O-O {if Black will include ...a6, the white bishop will retreat to e2 with the
same plan.} 9. Nf3 $1 {I have concluded that this is the best and also the
simplest continuation for White. It stops the Be5 idea for Black, keeps an eye
for the d7-d5 push and pretty much forces the black bishop away from the h2-b8
diagonal. This allows White to position his dark-squared bishop on f4 and g3,
enabling a lasting pressure on the weak d6 pawn.} (9. Nc3 {This automatic move
is a much more popular alternative which probably also is good if White can
improve his play.} Be5 10. Nf3 (10. Be3 d5 $1 $11) (10. Nde2 $5 $146) 10...
Bxc3 11. bxc3 d5 12. Ba3 dxe4 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Ng5 Qc7 $1 (14... Ng6 15. Qh5
h6 16. Bxf8 hxg5 17. Bc5 Nf4 18. Qd1 Qf6 19. Qd6 Qf5 20. Be3 $16) (14... Ba6
15. Qxd8 Rfxd8 16. Bxe7 Re8 17. Bc5 Bxf1 18. Kxf1 $14) 15. Qe2 Bf5 16. Nxe4
Bxe4 17. Qxe4 c5 $11) 9... Bc5 10. Nc3 {now as long as Black can't push d7-d5
and quickly regain the pawn, he will always have problems with the weakened
pawn.} a6 (10... d6 11. Bf4 Be6 12. Bg3 $1 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ga1c1,Gf1d1] ensuring
that} d5 {is met by} 13. Ng5 $1 $14) 11. Be2 d6 (11... b5 $2 12. Bg5 Bb7 13.
Nd5 Nb4 14. Rc1 Nbxd5 15. Rxc5 $16 {1-0 (30) David,A (2572)-Del Rey,D (2390)
New Delhi 2015}) 12. Bf4 Be6 13. Rc1 Ng6 14. Bg3 Nge5 15. Qd2 Re8 16. Rfd1 $14
{[%csl Rd6] It's obvious that Black has not equalized the game and White has
an easy game here.} *

