1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Qb6 $6 {[%cal Rc5d4,Rc6d4,Rb6d4] early jumps with
the queen are rarely good - Black does his best to stop any d2-d4 ideas for
the time being, however by doing so he wastes valuable time to develop his
pieces.} 4. Nc3 e6 {[%cal Rg8e7]} (4... Nd4 $6 5. Nxd4 cxd4 6. Nd5 Qd6 {
strictly speaking, the only move not to get into greater trouble than Black
already is at the moment.} (6... Qxb5 $4 7. Nc7+) (6... Qd8 $2 {extremely
logical but there's one minor issue with the move...} 7. Qh5 $1 {[%cal Gh5e5,
Gd5c7] and suddenly at move 7 White has created some serious problems!} a6 $4 (
7... Nf6 8. Nxf6+ gxf6 9. Bc4 e6 10. O-O $16 {Black is still breathing, but
probably not for long.}) 8. Qe5 $1 f6 9. Nc7+ Kf7 10. Qd5+ {[%cal Gc7e6] 1-0 
(10) Smirin,I (2555)-Afek,Y (2365) Ramat Gan 1992}) (6... Qc5 7. c3 {also
doesn't look cheerful for Black.}) 7. d3 {[%cal Gc1f4]} Nf6 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9.
O-O e6 10. f4 Be7 11. f5 $14) (4... Nf6 5. e5 Ng4 (5... Ne4 $2 6. Nd5 $1 Qd8 7.
Qe2 $16) 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. O-O g6 8. d3 Bg7 9. Re1 Nh6 10. Ne4 $16 {and it's
quite obvious that the Black queen is misplaced at b6, and regarding the c5
pawn, some real problems might arise.}) (4... g6 $2 {with the inclusion of Qb6
and Nc3, now this standard move appears already to be a big positional mistake!
} 5. d4 $1 e6 (5... cxd4 6. Nd5 Qa5+ 7. Bd2 Qd8 8. Bf4 d6 9. Qxd4 $16) (5...
Nxd4 $2 6. Nxd4 cxd4 7. Nd5 Qc5 8. Bf4 $18) 6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. O-O f6 8. Bc4 Qc7
9. Nb5 Qb8 10. c3 a6 11. Nbd4 Nge7 12. Bh6 Rg8 13. Be3 Ba7 14. a4 Qc7 15. Ba2
Kf7 16. Qd2 Bb8 17. g3 $16 {1-0 (34) Zhigalko,S (2667)-Kurajica,B (2551)
Istanbul 2012}) 5. Bxc6 $1 {Of course, White is not going to wait for Black to
play Nge7 first so that he can recapture on c6 with a knight. Now Black is in
front of an uneasy decision.} Qxc6 {since Black is lagging behind in
development, it only makes sense for White to open the position.} (5... bxc6 {
[%csl Rc5,Rc6][%cal Gd2d3,Gb2b3,Gc3a4] typical of the particular pawn
structure, White's strategy relies on targeting the doubled c-pawn. The
inclusion of the Qb6 doesn't help Black at all.} 6. d3 d5 (6... f6 7. Nd2 d5 8.
Qh5+ g6 9. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Gc3a4,Gb2b3] and Black's pawns make an excellent
target practice for white pieces!}) (6... d6 {[%cal Re6e5]} 7. e5 $1 {
Disrupting Black's intentions to solidify in the center and open his
light-squared bishop. It doesn't matter what Black does, his doubled c-pawns
are eternally weak.}) 7. O-O Nf6 8. Re1 Be7 9. b3 Qc7 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bh4 Ba6
12. e5 Nd7 13. Bxe7 Kxe7 14. Qc1 g5 15. Na4 Qa5 16. c4 $16 {1/2-1/2 (31)
Ehlvest,J (2597)-Milov,V (2657) Merida 2006}) (5... dxc6 $6 {theoretically
this move is possible but doesn't make any sense in the particular setup.
White should be careful not to allow Black to play e6-e5.}) 6. d4 {Black has
to take on d4, otherwise White will proceed with d4-d5} cxd4 7. Qxd4 {[%cal
Gc1f4,Ge1c1,Gf3e5,Ge5c4,Gc4d6] simple and strong - the queen is well placed in
the center for future operations, and White can already target the weak d6
square. Black has to be very careful.} (7. Nxd4 {probably is also just as good,
but in my opinion, this position is easier to misplay than the mainline.}) 7...
d6 (7... b5 $5 {an aggressive approach to solve opening problems sometimes
give good results - now White has to be precise to claim an advantage in the
opening, even if it requires a piece sacrifice!} 8. O-O Bb7 (8... b4 $6 9. Nd5
$1 {a classical motif in the Sicilian defense - White sacrifices a knight to
get to the black king. Black doesn't have a great choice - the knight on d5
doesn't allow Black to continue the development at the kingside.} exd5 (9...
Bb7 10. Re1 $16) 10. exd5 Qc5 11. Re1+ Kd8 12. Qxc5 $1 {a rare exception -
White very quickly regains material with some interest.} Bxc5 13. Ne5 Kc7 14.
Nxf7 Bb7 15. Nxh8 Rf8 16. Be3 Bxe3 17. Rxe3 Nf6 18. Re7 Rxh8 19. Rxg7 $16 {
with excellent winning chances for White - the pawns at the kingside are going
to march forward sooner or later.}) 9. Rd1 Nf6 10. Ne5 Qc5 11. Qxc5 Bxc5 12.
Nxb5 Rc8 13. Nd3 Nxe4 14. Nxc5 Rxc5 15. Nxa7 Rxc2 16. f3 Nf6 17. Nb5 Ke7 18.
Nd4 Rc7 19. a4 $14 {With great practical problems for Black}) (7... Nf6 8. e5
$1 Bc5 9. Qd3 Nd5 (9... Ng4 10. Ne4 $14) 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. Qxd5 exd5 12. Bf4
$14) 8. Bg5 {disrupting Black's development and preparing the long castle.} f6
{now that the black knight can no longer go to f6, the white bishop can
retreat to e3 - job's done!} (8... h6 9. Bh4 {[%cal Gh4g3,Ge1c1]} f6 (9... Bd7
10. O-O-O e5 11. Qd3 Rc8 12. Nd2 Ne7 13. Nf1 b5 14. Ne3 $14) 10. O-O-O e5 11.
Qd3 Ne7 12. Nb5 Ng6 13. Bg3 $14 {Black is losing a pawn and doesn't have
sufficient compensation for it.}) 9. Be3 Ne7 10. O-O-O Ng6 11. Qd2 $1 {[%cal
Gf3d4,Gf2f5] White frees the d4 square for the knight thus Black's response is
almost forced.} (11. Nd2 b5 12. f4 Bb7 13. f5 e5 14. Qd3 b4 15. Nd5 Ne7 16.
Nxb4 Qc7 17. Nc4 Nc8 18. Nd5 {1-0 (28) Graf,A (2610)-Pambalou,F Korinthos 2001}
) 11... e5 (11... Ne5 $2 12. Nd4 Qd7 13. f4 Nc4 14. Qd3 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Be7 16.
f5 $18) 12. Qd3 $1 {[%cal Gf3d2,Gb2b3,Gc3d5,Gd2c4] The black knight from g6
can no longer jump to e5, so White can start working on conquering all of the
weak light squares in the center. White is much better.} *

