1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Qc7 {This rare move probably serves only one real
purpose - to lead a well prepared White player out of known theory steps. In
most occasions, the early queen placement on c7 can be questioned.} 4. Nc3 {
of course, since the knight can jump to d5 and bother the black queen, why
not? In the main lines this would not be possible.} Nf6 (4... e6 $5 {a tricky
idea - Black goes for the Nge7 idea to push out the white bishop from b5 by
playing a6 and then recapturing on c6 by the second knight. However, by doing
this Black inevitably stays behind in development.} 5. O-O Nge7 (5... a6 6.
Bxc6 Qxc6 7. d4 {Transforms to positions, covered in the previous chapter.}) 6.
d4 $5 {This approach, excluding the moves Nc3 and Qc7 will be analyzed in
Chapter 6 - some ideas remain the same. It makes sense for White to go for
some sort of open Sicilian as the black knight on e7 feels misplaced for this
sort of position.} cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Nc6 {now if Nc3 and Qc7 weren't
included, White would have had Qc3 to keep an eye for the g7 pawn.} (8... a6 {
is not threatening anything, so} 9. Be3) 9. Bxc6 $5 {not mandatory - White can
also treat this position as Scheveningen variation and retreat with the queen,
then with the bishop to d3. The only difference is that there is a pair of
knights missing on the board.} bxc6 10. e5 {[%cal Gc3e4,Gc1f4]} d5 $1 (10... c5
11. Qg4 $1 Qxe5 $2 (11... Bb7 12. Bf4 h5 13. Qh4) 12. Bf4 {[%cal Gc3b5]}) 11.
exd6 Bxd6 12. Ne4 $5 ({Less clear is} 12. Qxg7 Bxh2+ 13. Kh1 Be5 14. Qg5 f6 15.
Qh4 Ba6 16. Rd1 Rg8 $13) 12... Bxh2+ 13. Kh1 {[%cal Gg2g3]} f5 (13... Be5 $6
14. Qc5 f5 15. f4 $1 fxe4 16. fxe5 Ba6 17. Rd1 $14 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gd1d6] with a
very unpleasant position for Black.}) 14. Qc5 $1 fxe4 15. Qh5+ Qf7 16. Qxh2 O-O
17. Be3 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc2c4,Ga1d1] with an equal position but White's position
might be easier to play. For example} Qe7 18. Rad1 e5 19. Qg3 Bf5 20. Rd2 Kh8
21. Rfd1 {and so on}) 5. d3 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gb5c6,Gc3e4,Gc1g5] a good move -
White slightly delays castling and prepares two ideas: either take on c6 and
play e4-e5, followed by Ne4, or go for Bc1-g5 and fight for the d5 square.} d6
{the best move - now the first White's plan of Bxc6 and e4-e5 doesn't work.} (
5... Nd4 6. Ba4 (6. Nxd4 $4 cxd4 7. Ne2 Qa5+ $19) 6... a6 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Ne2
Qa5+ 9. c3 dxc3 10. Nxc3 e6 11. O-O b5 12. Bb3 Bb7 13. Bd2 b4 14. Na4 $14 {
1-0 (60) Zhigalko,A (2572)-Kantans,T (2338) Warsaw 2011}) (5... e6 6. Bxc6 $1
bxc6 (6... Qxc6 7. e5 Nd5 8. Ne4 d6 (8... Be7 9. c4 Nc7 10. Nfg5 h6 11. Qh5 $40
) (8... b5 9. Nfg5 h6 10. Qh5 g6 11. Qh3 Be7 12. O-O $14) 9. c4 Nb6 10. b3 d5
11. Nc3 Be7 12. Bf4) (6... dxc6 $6 7. e5 Nd7 8. Qe2 $16 {[%csl Rd6]}) 7. e5 Nd5
(7... Ng4 8. Bf4 f6 9. Ne4 $14 fxe5 $2 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Qh5+ $18) 8. Ne4 f5 9.
Ng3 Be7 10. c4 $14) (5... a6 6. Bxc6 bxc6 {[%cal Re7e5]} (6... dxc6 {[%cal
Re7e5]} 7. e5 Nd5 8. Ne4 Bg4 9. O-O Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Qxe5 11. Re1 e6 (11... f5 12.
Qxf5 $1 Qxf5 13. Nd6+ Kd7 14. Nxf5 $14) 12. Bg5 Qc7 13. c4 h6 14. Bh4 Nf4 15.
Bg3 g5 16. Nf6+ Kd8 17. Rad1 Kc8 18. d4 Bg7 19. Nh5 Bxd4 20. Nxf4 gxf4 21. Bxf4
$16 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Gb2b4]}) (6... Qxc6 7. e5 Nd5 8. Ne4 {[%cal Gc2c4]}) 7. e5
Nd5 8. Ne4 {[%cal Gc2c4]}) (5... g6 {For the particular setup the queen on c7
has nothing to do and constantly jumps under Nd5 tempo in many variations.} 6.
O-O Bg7 7. Re1 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gc3d5]} e5 8. Bc4 d6 9. Nd2 O-O 10. Nf1 Be6 11. Bg5
$14 {[%cal Gf1e3,Ge3d5]}) 6. O-O e6 {anything else and Black's position looks
already rather unpleasant. Here I would like to suggest to you a fresh new
idea.} (6... a6 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 (7... Qxc6 8. e5 {looks already rather
unpleasant for Black as he will be struggling to finish his development.}) 8.
e5 dxe5 9. Re1 Bg4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 $14 {[%cal Gf3g3] and White inevitably
wins back the pawn}) 7. Bg5 {the whole point of this standard move is to lure
out the black bishop on e7. Several years ago Michael Adams won a nice game
against Sergei Zhigalko by playing 7.Bxc6+ and 8.e5 first. In the game
Zhigalko correctly retreated with the knight and got a good game.} (7. Bxc6+
Qxc6 8. e5 Nd7 $1 9. d4 d5 10. a4 b6 {and we've reached some kind of a French
defense structure - Black is perfectly fine here.} 11. Re1 h6 $11 {1-0 (40)
Adams,M (2704)-Zhigalko,A (2587) Rijeka 2010}) 7... Be7 {after this move we
can repeat the idea shown in the Adams - Zhigalko game with the inclusion of
Bg5 and Be7. Now Black doesn't have the option to retreat with the knight!} (
7... Bd7 $5 {Perhaps this is a more cautious response. However by doing this
Black voluntarily goes to a typical Rauzer variation position where I still
prefer White.} 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. d4 $1 {[%cal Gd4d5]} cxd4 11. Nxd4
{[%cal Gd1h5,Gd4e6,Gf2f5]} h5 {probably a necessity as the Qh5 threat very
often is annoying. Here I found a small improvement of what's been played
before.} 12. Qd3 $5 $146 {[%cal Gd4b5,Ga1d1] with a simple threat - attack the
d6 pawn and trade off one of the bishops.} (12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Qf3 Be7 14. Ne2
d5 15. c4 dxe4 16. Qxe4 f5 $11 {1-0 (45) Kryvoruchko,Y (2640) -Zhigalko,S 
(2679) Wroclaw 2011}) 12... a6 13. Nxc6 Qxc6 (13... bxc6 {this is still
possible but now Black has made an extra weakness on a6, and the inclusion of
Qd3 is in White's favor.} 14. f4 h4 15. f5 h3 16. gxh3 $14 {[%csl Rf8][%cal
Gg1h1,Ga1d1] the white king feels safer than his black opponent, and the white
knight is superior to the black bishop. The pawn on b2 is irrelevant.}) 14. Ne2
$1 {[%cal Ge2d4] The knight has nothing to do on c3 anyway.} h4 (14... Rc8 15.
c3) 15. Nd4 Qb6 16. h3 Rg8 17. c4 Bh6 18. Nf3 $14 {with a clear edge for White.
}) 8. Bxc6+ $1 Qxc6 (8... bxc6 {[%cal Re6e5] since Black is threatening to
close the center with e6-e5, White's reply is almost forced.} 9. e5 $1 {
a beautiful positional pawn sacrifice!} dxe5 10. Re1 {it is entirely possible
that White might not win back the e5 pawn. However, the c5 pawn also makes a
nice target, and the black bishop on c8 feels clumsy. From a practical point
of view, this position is very unpleasant for Black.} Bd6 (10... Nd7 11. Bxe7
Kxe7 12. Qe2 f6 13. Nd2 {[%csl Rc5,Re7][%cal Gc3e4,Gd2b3,Gf2f4]}) 11. Nd2 $1 {
[%cal Gg5h4,Gh4g3,Gc3e4,Gd2b3,Gd2c4]} Nd5 (11... h6 12. Bh4 Ba6 13. b3 Be7 14.
Nf3 Nd7 15. Bxe7 Kxe7 16. Qc1 $16 {[%cal Gc1a3,Gc3e4,Gd3d4]}) (11... Ba6 12.
Nce4 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 O-O 14. b3 $14 {[%csl Ra6,Rc5,Re5][%cal Gd1d2,Gd2c3]}) 12.
Nce4 f6 (12... O-O 13. Nxd6 Qxd6 14. Ne4 Qc7 15. Nxc5 $14) (12... Be7 13. Bxe7
Qxe7 14. Nb3 $14) 13. Nxd6+ Qxd6 14. Ne4 Qe7 15. Bd2 $14 {[%csl Rc5][%cal
Gc2c4,Gd2e3]}) 9. e5 {now there is no good retreat with the knight, and Black
has no choice but to take the pawn.} dxe5 (9... Nd5 $6 10. Nxd5 Bxg5 11. Nxg5
Qxd5 12. Qh5 $1 g6 13. Qh6 {[%cal Gh6g7] it might not be obvious from the
first sight, but Black here is already lost! The white queen together with the
knight makes a powerful team.} Qxe5 14. d4 $1 {closing the long diagonal and
fighting for the control of the g7 square.} cxd4 {[%cal Re5g7]} (14... Qxd4 15.
Rad1 Qxb2 16. Rxd6 $18) 15. Rfe1 Qf6 (15... Qf5 16. Qg7 $18) 16. Ne4 Qe7 (16...
Qe5 17. f4 {[%cal Gh6g7]}) 17. Qg7 Rf8 18. Qxd4 $18) (9... Ng8 10. Be3 $14 {
[%csl Rg8][%cal Gd3d4,Gc3e4]}) 10. Nxe5 Qc7 11. f4 $1 {White game is very easy
and logical.} O-O 12. Qf3 $14 {the following moves are not forced and
illustrate how the game might be proceeding. White is better here without
question.} Bd7 13. Rae1 Rac8 $6 {[%cal Rd7c6]} 14. f5 exf5 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16.
Nd5 Qd6 17. Nxd7 Qxd7 18. Nxf6+ gxf6 19. Qxf5 $16 *

