1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 {not a very popular continuation despite it's
flexibility. Depending on what White will play, Black, can choose from several
setups.} 4. Nc3 {usually the simplest and the most logical moves are the best
ones. White is postponing two decisions - whether to take on c6 and keep d2-d4
also as an option.} g6 {it's quite a weird way for Black to go for the best
setup in the Rossolimo with the following fianchetto of the bishop. The knight
on f6 becomes a prime target to win a few tempos for White, however, there are
quite a lot nuances.} (4... Qc7 {Probably is the main move here, but it
transforms to the main line of the Chapter 4.}) (4... Nd4 {in the spirit from
a particular English Opening line (with reversed colors) however here White
has an extra tempo which makes a difference.} 5. e5 $1 Nxb5 6. Nxb5 Nd5 7. Ng5
$5 {[%cal Gd1f3,Gf3d5,Gf3f7] Not mandatory but what an unexpected resource!
Suddenly the blatant idea of Qf3 is not easy to parry. Oddly enough, there's
more than several games already played in this line!} ({Of course, there is
nothing wrong also with the simple} 7. O-O a6 8. Nc3 Nxc3 9. dxc3) 7... f6 (
7... e6 $2 8. Ne4 {[%csl Rd6]}) 8. Qf3 (8. Qh5+ {a continuation for all the
tricksters out there - a completely playable alternative} g6 9. exf6 $1 {
[%cal Gf6f7]} Nxf6 10. Qe2 {[%cal Gb5d6]} e6 11. h4 a6 12. Nc3 {[%cal Gh4h5,
Gd2d3,Gc3e4] and also this position at least visually doesn't look great for
Black.}) 8... fxg5 (8... Nc7 {After this move White by force wins a pawn.} 9.
exf6 exf6 10. Qe4+ Ne6 11. Nxh7 d5 12. Qg6+ Ke7 (12... Kd7 13. Nxf8+ Qxf8 14.
d3 Qe8 15. Qxe8+ Rxe8 16. O-O a6 17. Na3 b5 18. c3 $14) 13. O-O $1 (13. Nxf8
Kxf8 $44) 13... Bd7 14. Nxf8 Kxf8 15. Nd6 Qe7 16. Nf5 Qe8 17. Qxe8+ Rxe8 18. d3
$14 {a pawn is a pawn after all.}) 9. Qxd5 a6 10. Nc3 e6 11. Qf3 {[%cal Ge1g1,
Gc3e4]} Qc7 12. Qh5+ g6 13. Qxg5 Bg7 14. f4 O-O (14... d6 15. exd6 Qxd6 16. d3
{possibly Black has some compensation for the lost pawn, but White's play is
effortless anyway.}) 15. d3 (15. Ne4 $1 b6 16. d3 Bb7 17. Nd6 $16) 15... b5 16.
Be3 Bb7 17. O-O c4 18. a3 Qc6 19. Rad1 a5 20. dxc4 {1-0 (28) Perunovic, M 
(2596)-Kardoeus,D (2229) Germany 2017}) (4... e5 $6 {a highly dubious
continuation as the main line hardly gives a satisfactory game for Black, and
there are no good alternatives instead of it.} 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nxe5 Nxe4 7.
Nxe4 Qd4 {the whole point of the combination - Black wins back the sacrificed
material and has two bishops. However, his king is too exposed.} 8. Qe2 $1 Qxe5
9. f4 $1 {[%csl Re8]} Qxf4 $2 {this brave move looks like a serious mistake,
and perhaps already here Black is lost. White doesn't go for a direct
discovered check, but prepares a deadly attack instead. However, also the
alternatives for Black here look bleak.} (9... Qe6 10. f5 Qe5 11. O-O Be7 12.
d3 {[%cal Gf5f6]} f6 13. Bf4 Qd4+ 14. Kh1 O-O 15. b3 $14 {[%cal Ga1e1,Gg2g4]}
Bxf5 $4 16. Ng3 {[%cal Gg3f5,Ge2e7]}) (9... Qe7 10. f5 g6 11. O-O Bxf5 12. Nd6+
Kd7 13. Qxe7+ Bxe7 14. Nxf5 gxf5 15. Rxf5 $14) 10. d4 (10. Nf6+ {the tempting
double check gives nothing but a perpetual.} Kd8 11. Qe8+ Kc7 12. Qxf7+ Kd8 13.
Qe8+ $11) 10... Qh4+ 11. g3 Qe7 {all forced} 12. Bg5 $1 {after this powerful
move I found no adequate defense for Black.} (12. O-O $2 {it's a little
strange that two of the best players in the World went for this line in 2003
and didn't know that it's close to losing.} f5 13. Nd6+ Kd7 14. Qxe7+ Bxe7 15.
dxc5 Bxd6 16. Rd1 Ke8 17. cxd6 Be6 18. Bg5 {1/2-1/2 (40) Anand,V (2753)
-Kramnik,V (2807) Monte Carlo 2003}) 12... f6 (12... Qe6 {after this move
White has to find several only moves to claim a big advantage - won't be too
difficult if you know it already beforehand! Without the knowledge, however,
it might be tough (if not impossible), especially to evaluate the consequences.
} 13. O-O $1 h6 (13... cxd4 14. Rae1 Kd7 15. Qf2 Kc7 16. Qxd4 b6 17. Bf4+ (17.
Nd6 Bxd6 {1/2-1/2 (49) Ristic,N (2420)-Bakic,R (2445) Niksic 1997}) 17... Kb7
18. Nd6+ Bxd6 19. Bxd6 $1 $18) 14. Rae1 $3 hxg5 15. Rxf7 $3 {[%cal Ge2f2,Ge4g5]
after this move Black's position should collapse. White pretty much to
everything will respond with Qf2 and Nxg5.} Be7 16. Qf2 Qg6 17. Nxg5 $3 Qxg5
18. h4 Qd5 19. Rfxe7+ Kd8 20. dxc5 $18 {[%cal Ge1e3,Ge3d3]}) 13. O-O-O $3 fxg5
(13... Kf7 14. Rhf1 {[%cal Gg5f6,Gf1f6]}) 14. dxc5 $3 Qe5 (14... Kf7 15. Rhf1+
Kg8 16. Rd6 $1 {[%cal Ge2c4]} h6 17. Qc4+ Kh7 18. Qd3 Kg8 19. Qc4+ Kh7 20. Rf7
Qe5 21. Qd3 Kg8 22. Rxf8+ Kxf8 23. Rd8+ {1-0 (31) Zezulkin,J (2452)-Priborsky,
J (2359) Czechia 2007}) 15. Rhe1 Be6 16. Qh5+ (16. Qf2 {[%cal Ge4d6] is
perhaps simpler}) 16... g6 17. Qxg5 Qxg5+ 18. Nxg5 Bh6 19. Rxe6+ Kf8 20. h4
Bxg5+ 21. hxg5 $18 {1/2-1/2 (37) Plaskett,H (2435)-Murey,J (2500) Gausdal 1986}
) (4... e6 $6 {this setup would make sense if Black would continue with Ng8-e7
and follow by a7-a6. Here the knight is already on f6, and Black creates a
serious weakness on d6.} 5. e5 Nd5 6. O-O Be7 (6... Nxc3 7. dxc3 d5 8. exd6
Bxd6 9. Ng5 $1 $14 {[%cal Gd1h5,Gd1d3,Gg5e4,Gc1e3]}) 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. Ne4 {
[%cal Gc2c4,Gd2d3] typical structures were already covered in previous
structures - Black is struggling.}) 5. h3 $1 {[%cal Ge4e5] I like this quiet
move - White is threatening to play e4-e5, and the black knight won't have a
good square to retreat. Of course, it is possible to play e4-e5 immediately
but I evaluate the arising position as good for Black} (5. e5 Ng4 6. Bxc6 dxc6
7. d3 Bg7 8. Bf4 Nh6 9. Ne4 Bg4) 5... Bg7 {certainly not the only move but by
doing this Black shows that he is not afraid of the e4-e5 push and will
consider it as a target instead. Good news for White is that he has only one
excellent continuation here} (5... Nd4 6. e5 Nxb5 7. Nxb5 Nd5 8. O-O Nc7 9. a4
$1 $14 {[%cal Gd2d4]}) (5... Qc7 $5 {[%cal Rc6e5,Rc7e5]} 6. O-O Bg7 7. Re1 e5
8. d3 $14 {[%cal Gc1g5,Gc3d5,Gb5c4]}) (5... d5 6. d3 $146 {[%cal Gb5c6,Gd1e2,
Ge1g1]} dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Bd7 9. Be3 b6 10. Kc1 $14 {[%cal Gh1d1]}) 6.
e5 {Of course! If you can force the black knight to retreat to an awkward
position, or perhaps even win a few tempos, it's already a great move!} Ng8 {
Black doesn't mind losing two tempos with the knight as he is threatening to
win the e5 pawn. To protect it, a typical follow-up would be Bxc6, but then
Black will get a normal position.} (6... Nh5 $6 7. Bxc6 dxc6 8. d3 {[%cal
Gg2g4]} f5 9. exf6 Nxf6 {this is hardly what Black would want to do this is
line with so many weaknesses}) 7. O-O $1 {the only way to try to punish Black
for his chosen strategy - Black is lagging behind in development so in White's
best interest is to go for quick development and an immediate attack.} (7. Bxc6
dxc6 8. O-O Nh6 9. d3 Nf5 10. Re1 Nd4 {Black is very flexible and has two
bishops. It doesn't look like a promising position for White.}) 7... Nxe5 {
not mandatory but a very principled reply} (7... Nh6 {is a serious alternative
- perhaps White will take on c6 after all?} 8. d4 $1 {White has managed to
save his light-squared bishop which might become an important piece later on.
Please note that also by not taking on c6 Black is struggling to finish his
development.} cxd4 (8... Nxd4 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Qxd4 {White's advantage is
obvious}) 9. Ne4 $1 $146 {a logical novelty - previously White had twice taken
on d4, thus sacrificing the e5 pawn.} O-O 10. Re1 $36 {With an initiative for
White. The following line is not forced and it merely illustrates what might
be White's strategy. White has more than enough compensation for the
sacrificed pawn, and the black knight on h6 feels awkward and can become a
quick target after Bf4 or Bg5 and Qd2, followed by g2-g4.} Qb6 11. Bc4 Qc7 12.
Bb3 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. Bg5 Kh8 15. f4 Qc7 16. Bxe7 Re8 17. Bd6 Qc6 18. Be5
Rxe5 19. fxe5 Bxe5 20. Qd2 $14) 8. Nxe5 Bxe5 9. Re1 Bg7 (9... f6 {While the
engines approve of this move, it just feels wrong. White will get a good game
with pretty much every continuation, while for Black it's problematic to
finish the development. Here are at least two interesting and energetic
continuations for your consideration. Both of them lead to a very complex game.
} 10. d4 $5 (10. b4 $5 a6 11. Bf1 cxb4 12. d4 Bb8 13. Nd5 $13) 10... cxd4 (
10... Bxd4 11. Ne4 a6 12. Ba4 b5 13. c3 d5 $1 (13... Be5 14. Bc2 {[%cal Ge4c5,
Ge4g5,Gg5h7,Gd1d5]}) 14. Bc2 dxe4 15. Bxe4 Bxf2+ 16. Kxf2 Qxd1 17. Rxd1 Ra7 18.
Be3 Rc7 19. a4 bxa4 20. Rxa4 Bb7 21. Bxb7 Rxb7 22. Rd2 $44) 11. Nd5 $40 {
[%cal Gf2f4,Ge1e5,Gd1e1]}) 10. d4 $1 {A second pawn sacrifice is almost a
mandatory follow-up for White} a6 {an important intermezzo for Black to get
rid of the bishop from b5 to gain access to the defensive move d6 or d5. Later
it might be already too late.} (10... cxd4 $6 11. Nd5 Kf8 (11... a6 $4 12. Bf4
$18 {[%cal Gf4c7,Gd5c7]}) 12. Bg5 (12. Qf3 {is also good and strong}) 12... f6
13. Bh4 e6 14. Qxd4 Kf7 15. Bg3 $1 $16 {1/2-1/2 (36) Ducarmon,Q (2466)
-Reinderman,D (2599) Delft 2016}) 11. Bc4 Bxd4 {Spanish WGM Sabrina Vega
Gutierrez is particularly fond of this line for Black - she has already played
it 3 times, and against a very good opposition. The results, however, are not
great.} (11... cxd4 $146 12. Bg5 $3 {[%cal Gg5e7,Gc3d5]} Nf6 (12... dxc3 13.
Qd5 $18) (12... d6 13. Nd5 Be6 14. Nxe7 $1 Be5 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Nd5 Qxg5 17.
Nc7+ Kf7 18. Nxa8 $16 Qd8 $6 19. Qf3+) (12... h6 13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. Nd5 O-O 15.
Nxe7+ Kh7 16. Qf3 d5 17. Bxd5 Be6 18. Bxb7 Rb8 19. Nc6 Bd5 20. Nxd8 Bxf3 21.
Bxf3 Rfxd8 22. Rab1 $14) 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 f6 15. Qxd4 e6 16. Rad1 Qe7 17.
Bd2 a5 18. Qb6 $16) (11... d5 {an interesting way to counter White's gambit.}
12. Bxd5 (12. Nxd5 $5 b5 13. Bf4 Ra7 14. dxc5 bxc4 15. Nb6 {also looks very
interesting!}) 12... cxd4 13. Be3 $1 Qb6 (13... dxc3 $4 14. Bxf7+) (13... Nf6
14. Qxd4 O-O 15. Bf3 $16) 14. Na4 Qf6 15. Bd2 Bd7 $4 (15... Qd6 16. Qf3 Nf6 17.
Bb3 O-O 18. Bf4 Qd8 19. Be5 $14 {[%cal Ga1d1]}) 16. Nc5 Bc6 17. Ne4 $1 Qe5 18.
Bxf7+ $1 {[%cal Ge4g5]} Kd7 19. Qg4+ Kd8 20. Ng5 h5 21. Qe6 {1-0 (21)
Rombaldoni,A (2484)-Libiszewski,F (2520) Porto Mannu 2013}) 12. Bf4 $1 {
the most precise continuation to keep the initiative going} (12. Nd5 {while
certain variations look effective if Black is prepared and plays precisely,
White's attack runs out of gas.} e6 $1 (12... d6 $2 {[%cal Rc8e6] exactly what
White was hoping for!} 13. Rxe7+ $1 Nxe7 14. Qxd4 $3 Kd7 (14... cxd4 15. Nf6+
Kf8 16. Bh6#) 15. Qg7 $1 (15. Qd3 Nxd5 16. Qxd5 Qf6 17. Bg5 Qf5 18. Qd2 Kc6 19.
Rd1 Qe5 20. c3 Bf5 21. f4 {1-0 (21) Edouard,R (2628)-Vega Gutierrez,S (2414)
Cap d'Agde 2016}) 15... Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Kc7 17. Bf4 {[%csl Rc7,Rd6][%cal Ga1d1,
Gg7c3,Gb2b4]}) 13. c3 Bg7 14. Bf4 d6 {I failed to find here anything
impressive for White. Black has two extra pawns, and White has to show
something for it.} 15. Qd2 {[%cal Ga1d1]} (15. Bg5 Qxg5 $1 16. Nc7+ Ke7 17.
Nxa8 b5 {it certainly looks that White is risking here more than Black.}) 15...
b5 16. Bf1 Bb7 17. Rad1 {probably White has just enough compensation for the
sacrificed pawns but certainly not more.} e5 18. Be3 Nf6 19. Nxf6+ Bxf6 20. a4)
12... d6 {the best response - Black has to be here very accurate.} (12... Bxc3
13. bxc3 e6 14. Qd6 Ne7 15. Qxc5 $14) (12... e6 $2 {very tempting but it has
an effective cure!} 13. Ne4 d5 14. Bxd5 $3 Qxd5 (14... exd5 15. Nxc5+ {[%cal
Gd1d4]}) 15. c3 Bxf2+ (15... Bg7 16. Qxd5 exd5 17. Nf6+ Kd8 18. Re8#) 16. Kxf2
Qxd1 17. Raxd1 f6 18. Nd6+ Ke7 19. Nc4 e5 20. Nxe5 $1 fxe5 21. Rxe5+ Kf7 22.
Rd8 $18 {[%cal Ge5e8]}) (12... Kf8 13. Qf3 Kg7 14. Bc7 $1 Qxc7 (14... Qf8 15.
Na4 $16 {[%cal Ga4b6]}) 15. Qxf7+ Kh6 16. Re4 {[%cal Ge4h4]} Nf6 17. Rxe7 Qf4
18. Ne4 Nh5 19. g4 $3 $16 Qxf7 (19... Bf6 20. gxh5) 20. g5+ Kg7 21. Rxf7+ Kg8
22. Nd6 $18) 13. Qf3 {now comes a sequence of the only good moves} Nf6 (13...
e6 14. Rad1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gc3e4,Gc3e2]}) 14. Bh6 Be6 (14... e6 15. Rad1 Rg8
{[%cal Rg6g5,Rg8g6]} 16. h4 $1 $40) 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Bg7 Rg8 17. Bxf6 Rf8 $1 (
17... Bxf6 18. Rxe6 Rf8 19. Nd5 $16 {[%cal Gf3e4,Ga1e1] looks just awful for
Black}) 18. Rxe6 Rxf6 19. Rxf6 Bxf6 20. Re1 Bxc3 21. Qxc3 {[%cal Gc3h8,Gc3b3]
White is still down a pawn, but it's only a matter of time when White wins it
back. The black king in the center feels uncomfortable.} Kd7 22. Qf3 {[%cal
Gf3b7,Gf3f7]} Rb8 23. Qg4+ $1 Kc6 24. Qa4+ $1 {the point of these checks is to
lure the black king as far as possible from the kingside where White will
regain the pawn and target the others.} Kb6 25. Qh4 e5 26. Qxh7 Qg8 27. Qe7 Kc6
28. Rd1 $14 {1-0 (45) Forcen Esteban,D (2561)-Vega Gutierrez,S (2408) Linares
2016. Objectively Black should hold, but it's easier to play with White. Also
White can organize a quickly passed pawn at the kingside should the queens be
exchanged at some moment.} *

