1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 {[%cal Rg8e7,Ra7a6] one of the two main
continuations for Black. He intends to play Nge7 in the next move so after the
following a7-a6 that he can recapture on c6 with a knight. Also, another idea
of this move is to fight for the center with the following d7-d5. Personally
with White I prefer not to take on c6, especially if Black is aware of recent
theoretical trends.} 4. O-O (4. Bxc6 bxc6 5. d3 {White shouldn't allow Black
to strengthen the center with e6-e5, followed by d7-d6.} Ne7 6. Qe2 d6 $1 {
[%cal Re6e5] White's next move is almost forced.} (6... Ng6 {[%cal Re6e5,Rd7d6]
after this old move White gets an advantage in every line.} 7. h4 $1 {stopping
e6-e5 and questioning the knight's placement.} Qc7 (7... h5 8. e5 f6 9. Qe4 Kf7
10. Nbd2 d5 11. exd6 Qxd6 {[%cal Rd6d5,Re6e5]} 12. Qa4 $14 {[%csl Rc5]}) 8. h5
Nf4 9. Qd2 e5 10. Qc3 Nxg2+ 11. Kf1 Nf4 12. Bxf4 exf4 13. h6 Rg8 14. Nbd2 $14 {
[%cal Ge4e5,Gd2e4]} d5 15. exd5 cxd5 16. Re1+ Be6 17. Ng5 O-O-O $6 18. Rxe6
gxh6 19. Nxf7 $1 (19. Qf6 {1/2-1/2 (54) Najer,E (2615)-Eljanov,P (2641) Warsaw
2005}) 19... Qxf7 20. Rhxh6 Bxh6 $2 21. Qxc5+ Kb8 22. Re7 $1 $18) 7. e5 Nf5 {
and Black has a good game - White is too slow to attack the doubled c-pawns
and Black is threatening to play Nf5-d4 as well, un-doubling the pawns.
However, that doesn't mean that this position for White is unplayable.}) 4...
Nge7 5. d4 $1 {Currently the most topical move! Even though White initially
went for a quiet Rossolimo, here the d2-d4 breakthrough can produce very
interesting results as the black knight on e7 and later on g6 feels misplaced
as it's not challenging White's center.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 Qb6 {after almost
everything else White will set up the Maroczy Bind structure - retreat with
the bishop on e2, and proceed with c2-c4, ensuring a long-lasting pressure. By
playing this move Black forces White to take on c6, however the actual value
of the queen on b6 is not clear.} (6... Ng6 7. Be3 Be7 (7... Qc7 8. Be2 {
[%cal Gc2c4,Gb1c3]} Nxd4 9. Bxd4 Bd6 10. g3 O-O 11. c4 b6 12. Nc3 Be7 13. Rc1
Bb7 14. f4 (14. Bf3 $6 {1/2-1/2 (18) Hou,Y (2653)-Ivanchuk,V (2728) Danzhou
2016}) 14... Bc5 15. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 16. Rf2 Bc6 17. Qd2 $14) 8. Be2 O-O 9. c4 {
[%csl Rg6] it should be quite apparent that for the particular structure the
knight on g6 has nothing to do as it's not helping to pressure the White's
center and go for the d7-d5 breakthrough.} Nxd4 10. Qxd4 b6 11. Nc3 Bb7 12.
Rad1 Bc6 13. Qd2 Bc5 (13... f5 $5 14. exf5 Rxf5 15. g3 $14 {[%csl Rg6][%cal
Gf2f4,Ge2f3]}) 14. Bxc5 bxc5 15. f4 f6 16. Qe3 Qb6 17. Rd2 Rab8 18. b3 Rfd8 19.
Bg4 Qb4 20. Rd6 $14 {1/2-1/2 (48) Areshchenko,A (2673)-Fedorov,A (2563)
Calimanesti Caciulata 2016}) (6... Nxd4 $6 {not a good plan for Black.} 7. Qxd4
a6 8. Be2 Nc6 9. Qc3 {[%cal Gc3g7] how should Black get rid of the annoying
pin? He is already behind in development.} b5 {[%cal Rc8b7,Ra8c8,Gc3g7]} (9...
Qf6 $6 10. Qxf6 gxf6 11. Be3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4,Rb7b5,Ga2a4]} d5 12. exd5 Nb4
13. Nc3 Nxc2 14. Rad1 Nxe3 15. fxe3 Bc5 16. Ne4 Bxe3+ 17. Kh1 f5 18. Nd6+ Kf8
19. Bh5 Kg7 20. Bxf7 exd5 21. Bxd5 $16 {1-0 (31) Yu,Y (2675)-Yap,K (2414)
China 2013}) (9... Qa5 10. Qxa5 Nxa5 11. Be3 Be7 12. a4 O-O 13. Nd2 $16 {
[%cal Gc2c3,Gb2b4,Ga4a5,Gd2c4]}) 10. a4 b4 11. Qg3 {[%csl Rb6,Rd6][%cal Gb1d2,
Gd2c4,Gc1f4]} Bb7 (11... h5 $1 12. Nd2 h4 13. Qe3 h3 14. g3 $14 {[%cal Gd2c4,
Gb2b3]}) 12. Bg5 Be7 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Qxg7 O-O-O 15. Nd2 Rhg8 16. Qh6 d5 17.
Nb3 $1 $16 {1-0 (44) Areshchenko,A (2664)-Krasenkow,M (2636) Baku 2014}) (6...
a6 7. Be2 {[%cal Gc2c4,Gb1c3,Gc1e3]} d5 {opening the position while being
behind in development can only mean one thing - White should be happy about it
and is clearly better.} (7... Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Nc6 9. Qc3 {transforms to a
previously covered variation.}) 8. exd5 Qxd5 (8... Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Qxd5 10. Qxd5 {
not mandatory - white queen can also retreat to c3, but Black is going to
force the queen exchange anyway after ...Nf5 and ...Qc5} Nxd5 11. c4 $1 Ne7 (
11... Nb4 12. Nc3 Bd7 13. Bf4 $14) 12. Bf3 Nc6 13. Be3 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gf1d1,
Ga1c1,Gc3a4,Ga4b6]}) 9. Be3 (9. Nf3 $5 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4]}) 9... Nxd4 10. Bxd4
Nc6 (10... e5 11. Bb6 Be6 12. c4 Qc6 13. Qb3 Rc8 14. Nd2 $14) 11. Bb6 Be7 12.
Nc3 Qxd1 13. Rfxd1 f5 14. Na4 $16 {1-0 (47) Muzychuk,A (2558)-Javakhishvili,L 
(2461) Doha 2016}) 7. Nxc6 dxc6 $5 {While not as popular as 7...bxc6, in the
2017 World Cup Slovenian GM Luka Lenic surprised Fabiano Caruana, by choosing
this continuation not only once, but boldly three times in a row! Fabiano was
not ready for it and the first two games ended with a draw. The third time,
however, was a charm - and that's the move I'm going to recommend to you!} (
7... Nxc6 8. Be2 $1 {[%cal Gc2c4,Gb1c3,Gc3b5,Gc1e3] again, the Maroczy Bind.}
Be7 9. c4 O-O 10. Nc3 Bf6 11. Nb5 a6 12. Be3 Qa5 13. Nd6 $1 Bxb2 14. Rb1 Be5
15. a4 Bxd6 16. Qxd6 Qxa4 17. Bb6 {and Black is completely paralyzed.}) (7...
Qxb5 $6 {A dubious move - Black quickly lands into trouble.} 8. Nd4 Qb6 9. Nc3
{[%cal Ga2a5,Gd4b5,Gb5d6] and the white a-pawn will march forward, causing
havoc in Black's camp.} a6 (9... Nc6 $6 10. Ndb5 {[%cal Gb5d6,Gc1e3]}) 10. a4 {
and White comfortably takes control of most of the dark squares at the
queenside. Black is powerless to stop it.} Nc6 11. Nb3 $1 {[%cal Ga4a5,Gc1e3,
Gc3a4,Ga4b6]} Qc7 (11... Na5 12. Be3 Qc7 13. Nxa5 Qxa5 14. Bd4 $16) 12. a5 {
[%cal Gc1e3,Ge3b6]} Bb4 {It doesn't look pretty but what else? Once the white
dark-squared bishop lands on b6, Black is pretty much paralyzed.} 13. Be3 Nxa5
14. Qg4 $1 {[%cal Ge3f4,Gg4g3] creating more weaknesses and preparing the
battery Bf4 and Qg3.} (14. Nxa5 $5 Bxa5 15. Rxa5 Qxa5 16. Qd6 f6 17. Bc5 $40 {
looks very promising, but it is against one of my rules - why go for
complications in a much better position?}) 14... g6 (14... Rg8 15. Nxa5 Bxa5
16. Bf4 d6 17. Qg3 $16) 15. Nxa5 Bxa5 16. Bf4 $16 {[%cal Gg4g3,Gf4d6] Black's
seriously weakened dark squares and the lack of the piece development should
be decisive.} d6 $2 17. Qg3 Bb4 18. Nb5 $18) (7... bxc6 {Will be covered in
Chapter 7.}) 8. Bc4 $1 {While it may not be obvious that the bishop should be
positioned exactly on c4, let me explain to you two setups that Black can
choose from. Either way, the black knight will go to g6, and after that: 1) he
can either go e6-e5, fixing the center and stopping f2-f4 for the time being.
In this scenario White has already positioned his bishop in a perfect spot,
also stopping Bc8-e6.2) Black will leave the pawn on e6 and bring his
light-squared bishop b7, followed by c5. The White bishop on c4 helps us to
threaten Black with the very annoying f4-f5.} Ng6 (8... Qc7 $6 9. f4 {White
can execute all the same ideas shown later and doesn't need to play Kh1 to
make f2-f4 happen.}) 9. Kh1 $5 {[%cal Gf2f4] When Caruana first played this in
the World Cup tiebreak against Lenic, it was a novelty and up to this day
remains the only game in this line. As far as my analysis goes, there is a
solid advantage in every single line for White. The purpose of the move is
very clear - immediately go for f2-f4.} e5 $146 {Since White has played Kh1,
it makes sense for Black to stop f2-f4. However, it's not so simple.} (9... Qc7
10. f4 Bd6 $6 {this is what Lenic played against Caruana in his 3rd game -
most likely he was still within his home preparation. The idea is to provoke
e4-e5 so that the f4-f5 threat is not so dangerous. However, that's not the
only plan White can choose.} (10... Be7 11. a4 {transforms to a variation
covered later.}) 11. e5 Be7 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Bd3 $1 {[%cal Gf1f3,Gf3h3,Gd1h5]
the bishop has nothing to do on c4 anymore, so it is relocated to d3. White is
ready to launch an immediate assault against the Black king.} b6 (13... b5 14.
Rf3 b4 15. Ne4 c5 16. Rh3 $16 c4 $2 17. Qh5 h6 18. Nf6+ Bxf6 19. exf6 cxd3 20.
fxg7 $18) (13... c5 14. Rf3 Rd8 (14... c4 15. Be4 Rd8 16. Qe2 {changes very
little in White's approach and only creates a yet another target on c4.}) 15.
Rh3 $1 {and Black can't take the bishop because of a simple checkmate.} c4 16.
Qh5 cxd3 17. Qxh7+ Kf8 18. Qh8+ Nxh8 19. Rxh8#) 14. Rf3 $146 {a much more
powerful continuation comparing to what was played in the game.} (14. a4 {
1-0 (45) Caruana,F (2807)-Lenic,L (2646) Tbilisi 2017}) 14... c5 15. Rh3 c4 16.
Qh5 h6 17. Be4 Bb7 (17... Rb8 18. Be3 $16) 18. Bxb7 Qxb7 19. f5 $1 exf5 20.
Bxh6 $1 gxh6 21. Qxh6 Bh4 (21... Rfd8 22. Qh7+ Kf8 23. Rf3 $18 {[%cal Ge5e6,
Gc3e4,Ga1f1]}) 22. Rxh4 Nxh4 23. Qxh4 Qc6 24. Rf1 Rae8 25. Rxf5 $18) (9... Be7
10. f4 O-O 11. Qe2 {White's plan is straightforward - finish the development
and eye for the f4-f5 threat. White should be ready that perhaps at some
moment Black might want to counterstrike with e6-e5 so that f4-f5 is met by
Nf4. However, by doing this Black is risking to lose a pawn or perhaps the
whole knight because of the g2-g3 threat.} Qc7 (11... e5 $6 12. f5 Nf4 13. Qf3
h6 14. Bb3 {[%cal Gc1f4]} Qc7 15. h4 $1 {[%cal Gg2g3] and Black will be
suffering big material losses.}) 12. a4 {a good prophylactic move never hurts
- White secures himself the space advantage and in some wild scenarios can
even transfer the queenside rook a1-a3-h3.} b6 13. Nc3 {Black is now at the
crossroads - should the light-squared bishop go to b7, after the f4-f5 push
the e6 pawn will no longer be protected. Thus a logical approach from Black is
to provoke the e4-e5 move first.} Bf6 (13... Bb7 14. f5 exf5 15. exf5 Ne5 16.
Bf4 Bd6 17. Bb3 Rae8 18. Rae1 $16) 14. e5 Be7 {this is the critical position -
White has to be very accurate to claim an advantage. First, it's important to
ensure that the black knight from g6 is not going to be rerouted to f5 via h4.}
15. g3 {[%csl Rg6]} (15. Rf3 $5 {[%cal Gc4d3,Gf3h3,Ge2h5] with the same
attacking motif also looks very good.}) 15... Bb7 16. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] with
a very annoying positional threat h4-h5} b5 (16... c5+ 17. Kh2 Rfd8 18. h5 Nf8
19. f5 $1 exf5 20. Rxf5 Ne6 21. Be3 $16 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Ga1f1,Ge2f2]}) 17. Bd3
c5+ 18. Kh2 b4 19. Ne4 Rfd8 20. b3 Nf8 21. Bb2 $14 {a dream position for
White! The queenside is fixed, most of the white pieces are optimally placed
for a future assault at the kingside.}) 10. Qf3 $1 {a paradoxical change of
plans - how to defend the f7 pawn?} Qc7 (10... f6 $6 {after this it's not
exactly clear how Black is ever going to castle so in White's best interest
might be reminding him that at the queenside White can launch a swift attack.}
11. a4 $16) 11. Rd1 $1 {[%cal Gc4f7,Gd1d8] suddenly it's not so easy to parry
the Bxf7 and Rd8 threat!} Nf4 {[%cal Rc8e6] it appears to be the only sensible
move.} (11... Bc5 $4 12. Bxf7+ Qxf7 13. Rd8+ Ke7 14. Bg5+ Ke6 15. Qb3#) (11...
h6 {while this stops the Bxf7 threat as in the end there is no Bg5 check, this
seriously weakens Black's kingside should he go for a short castle. Note that
the knight on g6 is unprotected due to the power of the white bishop on c4,
and the h6 pawn makes a fine target.} 12. Nc3 Bb4 13. Be3 O-O 14. Ne2 $14 {
[%csl Rg6,Rh6][%cal Ge2g3,Gg3f5,Gg3h5,Ge3h6,Gf3h5]}) 12. Bxf4 exf4 13. e5 $1
Qxe5 {Black didn't have a choice - the pawn on f4 was hanging.} (13... g6 14.
Qxf4 Bg7 15. Nd2 O-O 16. Nf3 $14) 14. Qb3 Be7 {strictly speaking, the only
move for Black.} (14... Qf5 15. Nd2 Be7 16. Re1 b5 17. Qf3 $1 Rb8 18. Bd3 Qd7
19. Nb3 $16 {and Black is in real trouble. Short castle is impossible because
of Qe4}) 15. Bxf7+ Kf8 16. Nd2 Qb5 17. Qxb5 cxb5 18. Bd5 $14 {[%cal Gd1e1,
Gd2f3,Ga1d1] while Black has managed to trade off the queens, his position is
still very much vulnerable. White will quickly take control of the most of the
central squares and take the both open files with his rooks.} *

