1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 4. O-O Nge7 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Qb6 7. Nxc6 bxc6 {
The most challenging approach - Black is fighting for the center and also
opens the b-file for future operations.} 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gc2c4,Gb1c3] The main
move - White yet again is setting up the Maroczy Bind which appears to be the
universal recipe for the best Sicilian approach! It is also important to note
that on d3 the bishop is not blocking the white queen to jump to the kingside 
(in most occasions to h5) in one move.} Ng6 {the only reasonable move Black
has here} (8... d5 $6 {Here this typical push doesn't really work for Black.}
9. Nc3 Ng6 (9... Bb7 10. Re1 {and Black will have a hard time to finish the
development.}) 10. exd5 cxd5 (10... exd5 11. Re1+ Be7 12. Bg5 $16) 11. Bb5+ $16
) (8... c5 $2 {[%cal Re7c6] The idea to put the knight on the alternative c6
square doesn't work.} 9. b3 Nc6 10. Bb2 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gb1a3,Ga3c4]}) 9. c4
Be7 {The most popular choice by Black.} (9... Bc5 {[%cal Rd7d6,Re6e5] Black
would want to take control of the central d4 square and strengthen it with
d7-d6 and e6-e5. In reality, he is too slow to do it.} 10. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3a4]
now Black has to do something about the Na4 threat - the dark-squared bishop
is too precious to be traded away for a knight, at least at this moment.} Qc7 (
{the same is after} 10... Bd4 11. Na4 {and probably there is not a big
difference where the queen goes as Black should push the d-pawn sooner or
later in order to activate the bishop on c8.} Qc7 {transforms to the covered
line}) 11. Na4 Bd4 (11... Be7 $6 {makes no sense as White gets the same
structure, with only a much more passive black bishop.} 12. c5 $14) 12. c5 $1 {
[%csl Rc6,Rd7] By doing this White ensures that the black pawn structure will
be crippled no matter what Black does. I didn't find equality for Black in any
lines.} O-O 13. Re1 $1 $146 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gd3f1,Gg2g3] my proposed improvement
- the bishop on d4 should be exchanged, and White will always enjoy a better
pawn structure. Depending on the situation, g2-g3 might be a good idea to
limit the black knight's possibilities at g6, and the bishop from d3 can be
rerouted from d3 to f1.} ({Previously in this position was played} 13. Kh1 e5
14. Bc4 d6 15. f4 Be6 16. Qd3 $6 Bxc4 17. Qxc4 d5 $1 18. exd5 cxd5 19. Qd3 Qc6
$17 {0-1 (37) Vasquez Schroder,R (2553)-Ynojosa Aponte,F (2395) Medellin 2017})
13... d6 (13... Rb8 {doesn't stop White's plan} 14. Be3 $1 Bxb2 15. Nxb2 Rxb2
