[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb2b3,Ga1c1,Gg2g3]}) 17. Rc1 $14 {with a solid advantage for
White, for example,} Ne5 18. Nc5 a5 19. Qd2 {[%csl Rc6,Rd4][%cal Gf2f4,Gc5d3]})
16. Bf1 $1 {a good prophylactic move to increase more tension to the center
and also remove the Bc8-d7 threat.} Rd8 (16... Rb8 17. Rc1 Rd8 18. b3 Bxe3 19.
Qxd6 Bxf2+ 20. Kxf2 Rxd6 21. Red1 $1 Rxd1 22. Rxd1 Bb7 23. Nxc5 Bc6 24. b4 $14
{White's chances are better due to the more active pieces and possibility to
organize a passed pawn at the queenside.}) (16... Bd7 $6 17. Nxc5 $1 Bxc5 18.
Bxc5 Qxc5 19. Qxd7 $16) 17. Qc2 {[%cal Ga4c5]} (17. Rc1 Ba6 $1 18. Bxd4 Bxf1 (
18... cxd4 $4 19. e5 $18) 19. Bxc5 Qe5 20. Qf3 Bb5 $11) 17... Ne5 {[%cal Re5g4]
} 18. h3 Nd7 19. Rad1 e5 20. Rc1 Rb8 21. b3 $14 {[%csl Rc5]}) (9... Bd6 {
An original attempt to slow down the f2-f4 push and also provoking g2-g3 which
would not allow White to start a swift initiative at the kingside by means of
