1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {Finally, we're onto the main move in the
Rossolimo! In most of the lines, Black remains extremely solid and hopes to
capitalize on White's errors. If Black plays perfectly, objectively there is
no advantage for White, just perhaps a slightly easier game or at least a
clear gameplan.} 4. Bxc6 {In my eyes, the most principal and currently also
the most topical continuation in the Rossolimo. Black has two choices - play
more solid or be aggressive.} ({The main alternative} 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 Nf6 6.
e5 Nd5 7. Nc3 Nc7 8. Bxc6 dxc6 9. Ne4 {although has some venom, is relatively
harmless for Black, and currently not so popular.}) 4... dxc6 {Black aims for
a peaceful position which includes a lot of maneuvering and positional
understanding. While not as popular as it's aggressive cousin 4...bxc6, the
whole system has some resemblance to a brick wall that White is trying to
break through.} (4... bxc6 {will be covered in Chapter 9.}) 5. d3 Bg7 ({
if Black wants to trade the light-squared bishop, he has to do it right now.
To be honest, there is no good reason to do it as the exchange is in White's
favor.} 5... Bg4 6. Nbd2 $1 {ensuring that a knight will remain on f3 no
matter what Black does.} Bg7 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Nxf3 Nf6 9. O-O Nd7 10. Be3 b6 11.
c3 O-O 12. Qc2 e5 13. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] with a very pleasant position for White.
}) 6. h3 {Ensuring that Black can't trade the bishop anymore, while the other
knight will go to a more active c3 square.} Nf6 (6... e5 {if Black closes the
center so early, this gives White an opportunity to create some play at the
queenside, as the a1-h8 diagonal is now closed.} 7. O-O Qe7 {[%cal Rg8f6,Rf6d7]
a typical maneuver, first defending the e5 pawn, then bringing out the knight.}
(7... Ne7 8. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4]}) 8. a3 $5 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gb1d2,Gc1a3] certainly
not the only continuation, but a very tempting one! Black needs to decide
whether he will or will not allow b2-b4 push to happen.} Nf6 (8... a5 {stops
the b2-b4 threat for good but at a great cost - the b6 square is eternally
weak.} 9. a4 $1 Nf6 10. Na3 O-O 11. Nc4 Nd7 12. b3 b6 13. Bg5 $1 f6 14. Bd2 {
[%csl Rg7][%cal Gf3h2,Gf2f4] with better chances for White. If Black is ever
going to trade the knight on c4, White will respond with bxc4, followed by a
pressure at the b-file.}) 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. b4 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gd2b3,Gd1e1,Ge1c3]
Black can't take the pawn on b4 because of the Ba3 threat in the end. Also,
the first trade gives up too many squares for Black. Depending on the
situation, White can choose between Nc4 or Nb3, followed by expansion at the
queenside.} Nd7 (10... Re8 11. Nc4 Nd7 12. c3 Nb6 13. Na5 Be6 14. Bg5 Qc7 15.
Be3 Nd7 16. Ng5 Rad8 17. Qc2 h6 18. Nxe6 Rxe6 19. Nb3 cxb4 20. axb4 a6 21. f4
exf4 22. Bxf4 Qc8 23. d4 $16 {1-0 (38) Grischuk,A (2671)-Wirig,A (2304) France
2002}) (10... Nh5 11. Nb3 $5 cxb4 12. axb4 Nf4 13. Re1) (10... Rd8 11. Qe1 $1
cxb4 12. axb4 Qxb4 13. Ba3 {and White will regain the pawn with a good game.})
11. Nc4 b6 12. Qe1 Ba6 13. Qc3 Rae8 14. Re1 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gc3b3,Gb3a4] 1/2-1/2 
(54) Gharamian,T (2558)-Vavrak,P (2472) Cappelle-la-Grande 2008}) (6... b6 {
very often this move doesn't change anything in White's setup, and the
position will transpose to one of the covered lines with a different order of
the moves.} 7. O-O Nh6 $6 {[%cal Re7e5,Rf7f6,Rh6f7] while with this
extravagant move Black is planning to finish his development with e7-e5, f7-f6
and Nf7, it is also directed against the typical White's plan - if White will
proceed with the standard plan of Be3, Nh2, and f2-f4. The best way to deal
with it is to build up a battery of a bishop and a queen to chase away the
knight.} (7... e5 8. a3 {[%csl Gb1][%cal Gb2b4,Gb1d2,Gd2c4,Gd2b3,Gd1e1,Ge1c3]})
(7... Nf6 8. Nc3 {transposes to the main lines}) 8. a4 $1 {[%cal Ga4a5] a4-a5
is a very annoying positional threat and Black can't just yet to play e7-e5
because of Nxe5 and the knight on h6 is hanging. So, the reply is almost
automatic.} (8. Nc3 O-O 9. Nh2 $6 e5 10. f4 $6 f5 $1 {and suddenly the
awkwardly positioned knight is a key piece in Black's position!} 11. fxe5 Nf7 {
and only Black can be better because of the two bishop advantage.}) 8... a5 {
In 2009 Viktor Bologan in his game against Sergei Zhigalko employed a new idea
9.Be3!? which saw several repeats after that. Black's game can be improved,
and with the help of the engines, I found an even better move.} 9. Bf4 $1 {
[%cal Gd1c1,Gc1h6] it appears to be stronger as it brings a yet another idea
to the table - meet 9...f6 with 10.e5! With the bishop on e3 it would not be
possible.} (9. Be3 f6 10. Na3 e5 11. Nc4 Be6 12. Nfd2 {[%cal Gb2b4,Ga4a5]} Ra6
13. f4 exf4 14. Bxf4 Nf7 15. Qf3 {1-0 (79) Bologan,V (2687)-Zhigalko,S (2587)
Budva 2009}) 9... Bxb2 $6 {this almost never works for Black - the extra pawn
is irrelevant and the b-file will be used for the invasion of the white pieces.
} (9... f6 10. e5 $1 O-O 11. Nbd2 $14 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gf1e1,Gd2c4] and White
has a solid advantage, and an easy game - Black's chosen strategy looks like a
