14. Nxc6 Qd7 15. Nxe7 $1 {[%cal Gf4g5,Gf4e5]} Qd4 16. Qc1 Bxc4 17. Nc6 Qd7 18.
Ne5 Qe6 19. Nxc4 $16 {the dust has settled, Black has a strategically lost
position.}) 11. Qc1 {[%cal Gc1h6]} Ng8 12. Rb1 Nf6 13. Nc4 Nd7 14. Bh6 O-O 15.
Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Nxb6 Nxb6 17. Qb2+ f6 18. Qxb6 $16) (6... Nh6 $6 {the idea of
this awkward move will be described a move later if Black would play 6...b6
first and only then - 7...Nh6. Here it looks a bit early jump as in some
variations the pawn on c5 is unprotected.} 7. a4 $1 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gc1e3,
Rg7b2] similarly like a move later, it has two purposes: threaten to play Be3
and setup the Qd2 or Qc1 battery to bother the black knight on h6, and also
think about a4-a5 maneuver, gaining some space.} a5 (7... O-O 8. O-O {the
position can transpose if Black will play here 8...b6. After everything else
Black is slightly worse, and White can push a4-a5.}) 8. Be3 {[%cal Gd1c1,Gc1h6]
} Qb6 (8... Bxb2 9. Nbd2 $1 Ng8 (9... Bg7 10. Rb1 b6 11. Nc4 Ra6 12. Qc1 Ng8
13. e5 $16 {with a dominant position for White}) 10. Rb1 Bd4 11. Bxd4 cxd4 12.
Qc1 $16 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gc1b2,Gd2c4]}) (8... b6 9. Qc1 Ng8 10. Na3 $14 {
can hardly be called an opening success for Black.}) 9. Nbd2 Be6 10. b3 f5 11.
O-O Nf7 12. Rb1 O-O 13. Nc4 Qa7 14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Re1 e5 16. Bd2 $16 {0-1 (75)
Quesada Perez,Y (2627)-Belous,V (2567) chess.com INT 2018}) 7. Nc3 {Let us
stop here for the time being and let me explain where the game is heading. A
couple of points: 1) Black intends to play e7-e5, effectively closing the
center. Nxe5 in most occasions won't work because of a counter-attack Nxe4.
After Black has played e7-e5, he can strengthen the pawn with Qd8-d6, and then
maneuver the knight from f6-d7-f8-e6-d4, or an alternative route f6-h5-f4 or
g7-e6-f4. The maneuver might be possible without moving the e-pawn but then
Black will have to deal with the quick advancement of white f-pawn. 2) if
White continues with a short castle, Black proceeds with the same approach.
Thus by doing this White's only chance for an initiative would be the f2-f4
push. 3) If White proceeds with a long castle, Black is forced to go into an
offensive at the queenside by b7-b5-b4 and a7-a5-a4 and so on. Considering all
of this, the short castle seems to be the easiest option but keep long
castling as an alternative for your approach.} O-O (7... Nd7 $5 {[%cal Re7e5,
Rd7f8,Rh7h6,Rf8e6] This interesting alternative aims for a quicker e7-e5 push,
followed by Nd7-f8-e6. Black is postponing castling for the time being.} 8. Be3
e5 9. O-O Qe7 10. Qd2 Nf8 $1 {A more cautious move than 10...h6.} (10... h6 {
an ambitious approach} 11. Nh2 Nf8 (11... g5 $6 {[%csl Rf5,Rh5] At some moment
it might be possible that Black could stop White's advancement of the f-pawn
by playing g6-g5 but the price is too high - weakened f5 and h5 squares that
White can easily exploit with his knights.} 12. Ne2 $16 {[%cal Ge2g3,Gf2f3,
Gh2f1,Ge3f2,Gf1e3]}) 12. f4 exf4 13. Bxf4 Ne6 14. Bg3 $1 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gc3e4]
Much stronger than the standard 14.Be3 - White goes for an immediate attack at
the kingside, and Black has to be extremely accurate. It all started back in
2005 with a famous game by Alexei Shirov against Loek van Wely (blindfolded!)
and the game has seen numerous repeats since then.} Qg5 (14... Nd4 $6 {after
this Black is in trouble.} 15. Rae1 O-O 16. e5 Bf5 17. Ne4 Bxe4 18. Rxe4 h5 $2
(18... Nf5 19. Bf4 Kh7 20. Ng4 Rad8 21. Qf2 Rd5 22. Bd2 $16 {[%cal Gg4f6,Gd2c3]
} (22. b3 {1-0 (42) Lopez Martinez,J (2548)-Zaslavsky,M (2391) Rijeka 2010}))
19. Bh4 $16 Qe6 20. g4 Qxa2 21. gxh5 Qxb2 22. h6 Bh8 23. h7+ Kxh7 24. Bf6 {
[%cal Ge4h4,Gd2h6] 1-0 (24) Sutovsky,E (2650)-Baron,T (2415) Rijeka 2010}) 15.
Qe1 ({Certainly not} 15. Qf2 $4 Bd4) 15... Nd4 16. Qf2 O-O {it's all forced.} (
16... Be6 $2 17. Bh4 Qh5 18. Ng4 $16 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gg4f6] White develops a
very dangerous initiative - the knight jump to f6 is inevitable.}) 17. Bd6 {
forcing Black to sacrifice a piece for three pawns.} Bxh3 18. Bf4 $1 Qxg2+ 19.
Qxg2 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 Nxc2 21. Rad1 Rad8 22. Rf2 (22. Ng4 $6 h5 23. Nf2 Rfe8 24.
