for the knight.} 11. Bh6 Nh5 12. Ne2 f6 13. Bxg7 Nxg7 14. Nh2 Ne6 $11 {doesn't
look like an achievement for White.}) 8... Nd7 {[%cal Re7e5] Black intends to
play e7-e5 next move.} (8... e5 $6 {A typical mistake mixing up the positions
with or without including the Be3 and b7-b6 moves. Black loses a pawn but has
some compensation for it.} 9. Nxe5 Nxe4 10. Nxe4 Bxe5 11. Nxc5 Qd5 12. Ne4 f5
13. Ng5 f4 14. Nf3 $14 {[%cal Gc1d2,Gd2c3] 1-0 (52) Danielsen,H (2488)
-Eriksson,C (2130) Borup 2014}) (8... Nh5 {[%cal Re7e5] an original way to
stop the f2-f4 in advance but it gives White an unexpected resource.} 9. e5 $1
{[%csl Rh5][%cal Gg2g4]} Bh8 10. Ne4 b6 11. Bh6 Re8 12. Qd2 $14 {and comparing
to an alternate theoretical position, here Black has lost a few tempos which
can't be good.}) (8... Qc7 $5 {[%cal Re7e5] a good move - Black intends to
play e7-e5 by keeping the knight on f6.} 9. Be3 b6 10. Nd2 ({if the arising
position doesn't inspire you too much then you can allow Black to execute the
e7-e5 and Nh5 idea I've been advocating to avoid - the queen on c7 is placed
worse than on d6, but the difference is not great.} 10. Qd2 e5 11. Bh6 Nh5 12.
Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Ne2 f6 $6 14. Nh2 ({This particular order of the moves allows to
execute an unexpected idea} 14. g4 $1 Nf4 15. Nxf4 exf4 16. e5 $1 $16) 14...
Be6 15. b3 a5 16. a4 Rad8 17. f4 Nxf4 18. Nxf4 exf4 19. Rxf4 $1 {keeping
