13. Nc4 {and so on}) (8... b6 9. Bf4 $1 {if Black is not rushing with the
decision to play e7-e5, you can stop it for the time being. White can freely
switch to the common ideas with Qd2 and Bh6, or Nh2 and f2-f4.} (9. Be3 e5 $1 {
is something we want to avoid.}) 9... Ne8 10. Qd2 Nc7 11. Bh6 Ne6 12. Bxg7 Kxg7
13. Ne2 {[%cal Gf3h2,Gf2f4]}) 9. Be3 {Since Black can't setup e7-e5 and Nh5 in
time anymore, it's important to include Be3 before playing Nh2 and f2-f4.} (9.
Nh2 $6 c4 $1 10. dxc4 (10. d4 b5 $13) 10... Nb6 11. Qe2 Qd4 {and Black is more
than alright.}) 9... e5 {it will take a very good player to understand all of
the nuances for Black - by making standard moves it is very easy to misplay
this position as shown later.} (9... b6 10. Qd2 e5 11. Nh2 {transforms to the
variation covered later.}) 10. Nh2 {Freeing the way for the f-pawn advancement,
and the knight at some occasions can join the attack via g4. The best part is
that White can play the f2-f4 push whenever he feels ready, before that
improving the position with moves like Qd2, Rae1, and b2-b3. Black is
expecting f2-f4, intending to play exf4, followed by Ne5 and Be6. If there is
no immediate trade, he can run out of good moves.} Qe7 (10... b6 11. Qd2 Nf6 $5
{After this very interesting approach I will illustrate how a typical battle
of maneuvering might occur for both sides waiting for the proper moment to
play f2-f4.} 12. Rae1 $1 {Don't rush with f2-f4 - by doing it immediately will
give Black a good play.} Be6 (12... Nh5 13. g4 Nf6 14. f4 exf4 15. Bxf4 $14 {
[%cal Gf4g3,Ge4e5,Gc3e4]}) 13. b3 $1 a5 14. a4 $1 Ra7 $1 15. Ne2 $1 {at all
times Black has to figure it out when White is finally going to play f2-f4.}
Nh5 {after this it will be problematic for Black to reroute the knight to e5.}
(15... Nd7 16. Bh6 f6 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. f4 exf4 19. Nxf4 Bf7 20. Ng4 $14 {
[%cal Gd2c3,Gd2h6] Black's problems are far from over.}) 16. Bh6 f6 17. Bxg7
Nxg7 18. f4 {and White is pushing}) 11. Qd2 $1 {[%cal Ge3h6] a good
prophylactic move - the f2-f4 push now won't go anywhere, and White can
prepare it. Exchanging the dark-squared bishops before doing it might be a
good idea.} Re8 {[%cal Rd7f8,Rf8e6] very logical - Black plans to reroute the
knight from d7 to e6 so probably the best moment to execute the f2-f4 push
would be when the black knight will be at f8 so that it takes him yet another
tempo to move the knight to the freed e5 square.} (11... b6 12. Bh6 f6 13. Bxg7
Kxg7 14. Ng4 Kh8 15. f4 exf4 16. Qxf4 h5 17. Ne3 $14) 12. Bh6 {it makes sense
to remove your opponent's best defender before starting an attack.} f6 (12...
Bh8 $6 {[%csl Gh6] one of the most popular moves in the position to keep more
tension on the board. I still can't imagine how this is a good decision by
Black - the bishop on h6 should be a very annoying guest!} 13. Rae1 Nf8 {
[%cal Rf8e6] it is entirely possible that this is not a good move, but at
least it forces White to play f2-f4. Both players are waiting - White waits
for Black to play Nf8 so that he can proceed with f2-f4, and Black waits for
White to play f2-f4 so that he can position the knight to e5. The problem for
Black is that White has more waiting useful moves to add than Black. For
example,} (13... b6 14. b3 a5 15. a4 Ra7 16. Ne2 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 14. f4 exf4
15. Qxf4 Ne6 (15... Nd7 $2 16. Ng4 {clearly Black can't make it in time to
move the knight to e5.} Ne5 17. Bg5 $18) 16. Qd2 Nd4 {While visually Black
looks normal, he is already close to lost.} 17. Nd1 $1 Be6 18. c3 Nb5 19. e5 $1
{the kingside is wide open for an invasion.} Qd7 20. Nf2 {[%cal Gf2e4,Gf2g4]}
Bf5 21. Nhg4 Re6 22. Bg5 h5 23. Nf6+ Bxf6 24. Bxf6 Kh7 25. g4 {1-0 (30) Popov,
I (2608)-Nogerbek,K (2242) Astana 2017}) 13. Ne2 Nf8 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. f4 exf4
16. Rxf4 Be6 17. Raf1 Nd7 18. b3 Rf8 19. R4f2 {[%cal Gh2f3] a good position to
have after the opening. Black lacks an active play while White can eternally
pressure Black at the kingside, combining it with threats against the Black
king.} *

