1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 bxc6 {a much more aggressive approach
than 4...dxc6 - Black is fighting for control in the center and hopes to
exploit his two bishop advantage and the open b-file. Currently, this is the
most popular continuation in the Rossolimo, and among the top players, it is a
favorite choice for Boris Gelfand. The game is much more dynamic than after
the static 4...dxc6.} 5. O-O Bg7 6. Re1 {a very flexible move - White develops
a rook and waits for Black to choose his setup. The most popular choices: 1)
Black develops the knight on the paradoxical h6 square which is the most
aggressive and popular approach. White will proceed with c2-c3 and d2-d4
breakthrough in the center while Black will try to counter it with either
d7-d5 or f7-f5 - for that reason the knight on h6 appears to be better
positioned. 2) The black knight goes to f6 - White will proceed with e4-e5,
drive away the knight from the center and position the queen to h4 for
attacking purposes 3) Black closes the center with e7-e5 - White will crash
through with c2-c3 and d2-d4.4) Other waiting moves not to define where the
black knight will go until White shows his setup - moves like 6...Rb8 or 6. ..
d6} Nh6 {[%cal Rf7f5] the most popular continuation - the typical idea is to
play f7-f5 and if White closes the center with e4-e5, then reposition the
knight to f7 and either continue with d7-d6 or a more aggressive approach
e7-e6 and g6-g5!} (6... Nf6 {While currently not as popular as 6...Nh6, it is
perfectly playable. I think it contradicts the whole philosophy of the
variation. If Black plays 4...bxc6, he is seeking a dynamic play and doesn't
mind to enter sharp lines to play for a win. After 6...Nf6 many lines are
drawish where only White is playing for more. With an ever-increasing
competition an average GM in open tournaments is forced to play for a win with
both colors.} 7. e5 (7. c3 {is playable, but it forces the game too much} O-O
8. d4 d5 $5 ({or} 8... cxd4 9. cxd4 d5 10. e5 Ne4 11. Nc3 Nxc3 12. bxc3 $11) 9.
e5 Ne4 10. Nbd2 cxd4 11. cxd4 c5 12. dxc5 Nxc5 13. Nb3 Nxb3 14. Qxb3 d4 $11)
7... Nd5 8. c4 Nc7 {here White has a pleasant choice} 9. d4 {the main move -
after this maneuver the white queen is repositioned to h4 to bother the black
king.} (9. b3 $5 {an interesting alternative which is much less explored than
9.d4. The position everywhere is about equal, yet it is always White who is
pushing. Black doubled c-pawns make an excellent target in the long run.} Ne6 (
9... O-O 10. Bb2 d6 11. exd6 exd6 (11... Qxd6 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Nc3 Bg4 $6 (
13... Bf5 14. d4 Rad8 15. dxc5 Qxc5 16. Qc1 $14) 14. Ne4 Bxf3 15. Nxd6 Bxd1 16.
