Qb6 13. h3 Bxf3 (13... fxe5 $6 14. hxg4 Nxg4 15. Nc4 $1 dxc4 16. Qxc4+ Kh8 17.
Qe6 Rf5 18. Re4 Nf6 19. Rxe5 Rxf3 20. gxf3 Qxd4 21. Be3 Qxb2 22. Rc1 Rf8 23.
Rxc6 Ng4 24. Re4 Nxe3 25. Rxe3 $16 {1/2-1/2 (64) Vidit,S (2707)-Gelfand,B 
(2695) Poikovsky 2018}) 14. Nxf3 Nf5 15. e6 $1 {[%csl Rg7] otherwise, there's
no point going towards this direction} Rfc8 (15... Nxd4 16. Nxd4 Qxd4 17. Qxc6
Qb4 {looks normal but Black needs to remain accurate.}) 16. Qd3 Qb5 17. Qd1 c5
18. dxc5 Qxc5 19. Bf4 Qb4 20. Bh2 Nh4 $6 21. Nxh4 Qxh4 22. Qxd5 $16 {1/2-1/2 
(36) Lupulescu,C (2617)-Fier,A (2570) Rio Achaea 2018}) 11... exf6 {[%cal
Rc8g4,Rh6f5,Rd8b6] Black would want to increase some pressure to the d4 pawn
so including the next move makes sense.} (11... Rxf6 $6 {is just bad} 12. Bg5
Rf7 13. Nbd2 Qb6 14. Nb3 Bg4 15. Qd2 $16) 12. h3 {[%csl Ra7,Rc6][%cal Gb1c3,
Gc1f4,Ga1c1,Gc3a4] from here the game is much less forced. White's plan is
simple - Nc3, Bf4, Rc1 and target the weak c6 pawn by the means of Nc3-a4. If
the bishop can't go to f4, an alternative is b2-b3 and Ba3. The white queen
can be positioned on the a-file to target the weak a7 pawn. It is Black who
will have some practical problems to decide what to do - play solid or go
aggressive with the tempting h7-h5 and g5-g4 idea. By doing so, he will
eventually weaken even more squares. I will illustrate for you several
possible scenarios which are not forced but at least will give you a better
understanding of what to expect from this line.} (12. Nbd2 {White might try to
play without the h2-h3 move, but Black has forced his hand with} g5 {[%cal
Rg5g4]} 13. h3) 12... Nf7 {[%cal Rf7d6,Rg6g5,Rh7h5] a standard retreat - the
knight can be rerouted to d6 to control half of the board, or accelerate a
kingside attack with g6-g5 and h7-h5. Occasionally the knight can also jump to
g5, should the pawn on d4 be left unprotected.} (12... g5 {[%cal Rh6f5,Rh7h5]
Black could consider starting a kingside attack. However, nobody can get mated
solely by two pawns and a knight! White proceeds with his gameplan.} 13. Nc3
Nf5 $146 (13... g4 $6 {a bad decision - Black will be left with weaknesses.}
14. hxg4 Bxg4 15. Bf4 Qd7 (15... Nf5 $6 16. Qd3 {[%cal Gf3h2] a common
maneuver to get rid of the pin} Nd6 17. Nh4 {[%cal Gd3g3]} f5 18. g3 Bf6 19.
Ng2 $16) 16. Qd3 Rae8 17. Nh4 $14 {[%cal Gd3g3]}) 14. b3 {[%cal Gc1a3] since
the bishop can't get to f4 anymore, this is an alternative route to bring it
to life.} h5 (14... Qd6 15. Na4 Bd7 (15... h5 $6 16. Nh2 {[%csl Rh5]}) 16. Nc5
Rae8 17. Ba3 Rxe1+ 18. Qxe1 Re8 19. Qa5 $14 {[%csl Ra7]}) 15. Ba3 ({Here} 15.
Nh2 {gives nothing because of the backrank weakness.} Re8 $1) 15... Re8 16. Qd3
{a good typical place for the queen to connect the rooks.} Bd7 17. Na4 g4 $1 {
not an obvious pawn sacrifice} (17... Qc7 18. Nc5 Rad8 {[%cal Rd7c8]} 19. Nxd7
Qxd7 20. Bc5 $14 {[%csl Ra7,Rf5][%cal Gc5a7]}) 18. hxg4 hxg4 19. Nh2 Qa5 20.
Rxe8+ Rxe8 21. Nxg4 Re4 22. f3 $11 {at least visually the position looks
better for White. The engines mercilessly announce equality.}) 13. Nc3 Bf5 (
13... g5 {not only with the idea to attack the white king, but also to take
away the f4 square for white bishop.} 14. b3 Bf5 (14... h5 $2 15. Qd3 {[%cal
Gd3g6]}) (14... g4 $6 15. hxg4 Bxg4 16. Qd3 Qd6 17. Ne2 $14) (14... Qd6 15. Qd3
Bd7 16. Ne2 {[%csl Rf5,Rh5][%cal Gc1d2,Ge2g3]}) 15. Ba3 Re8 16. Rxe8+ Qxe8 17.
Qd2 Qd7 18. Re1 Re8 19. Rxe8+ Qxe8 20. Bc5) 14. Bf4 Re8 15. Rxe8+ Qxe8 16. Na4
Qe4 17. Be3 {[%csl Gd4] otherwise White might experience some problems with
the d4 pawn.} (17. Bh2 $6 Ng5 $1 {[%csl Rd4]}) 17... Qe7 18. Rc1 Rc8 19. Nc5
Nd6 20. Bf4 {[%cal Gd1a4] and White is pressing. The position remains equal.}
Ne4 21. Be3 Nd6 (21... Nxc5 $6 22. dxc5 $14 {[%cal Gf3d4] White gains a nice
outpost on d4.}) 22. Qa4 Nc4 23. Re1 Qc7 24. Bc1 {with a long maneuvering
battle.} *

