{[%evp 0,25,19,14,60,66,63,28,60,28,19,12,-10,3,2,-27,0,14,35,35,30,36,53,53,
53,54,52,22]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 bxc6 5. d4 $5 {I've worked
for you a new interesting alternate main line than what I wrote in the Chapter
9 - instead of going for a known line with a very symbolic plus I offer you a
lot of fresh ideas and positions and there's a good chance that it will catch
your opponent completely off-guard! There are a few lines where Black is very
close to equality but he has to be aware of them in the first place and make a
lot of accurate moves to get there.} Bg7 {the most typical response - Black is
postponing the decision to take the pawn since he can regain it easily with
Qa5+.} (5... cxd4 {a very commital move - I'd treat this as a signal that
Black is not surprised by the rare move.} 6. Qxd4 {Black is at the crossroads}
f6 $5 {[%cal Rg8h6,Rh6f7,Rf8g7,Re8g8,Re7e5,Rf6f5] a very interesting and
aggressive continuation. Black intends to start an offensive at the kingside
as soon as he will make a castle. The best setup for White is yet again a
Maroczy Bind.} (6... Nf6 {[%cal Rd8b6] a normal response - here we esentially
transform to one of the setups from the Chapter 9, only with a different order
of the moves - 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 g6 4.Bxc6 bxc6 5.0-0 Bg7 6.Re1 and now
Nf6 which is not so popular. 7.e5 Nd5 8.c4 Nc7 9.d4 cxd4 10.Qxd4. While it's
not exactly the same position, the ideas are the same. Here White actually is
not obliged to include Re1 and can proceed with the kingside attack ideas
immediately.} 7. e5 {[%cal Gd4h4]} Nd5 (7... Nh5 {hardly contributes anything
for Black as the knight will be rerouted to e6 anyway.} 8. O-O {and so on}) 8.
O-O Bg7 {it is entirely possible that Black can postpone this move so that
after the threat Qh4 and Bh6 Black has managed to save a tempo, however it's
not clear what should Black do instead of it.} (8... Qb6 $6 9. Qh4 $14 {
[%csl Rb6]}) (8... Nc7 9. c4 Ne6 10. Qh4 Rb8 11. Nc3 $14) 9. Qh4 $1 {[%cal
Gc2c4,Gb1c3,Gc1h6] exactly in this order to play c2-c4 afterwards and thus
eliminate the fork idea on c2. White's idea is very simple - if Black castles,
play Bh6, followed by Ng5 with a strong attack. Black has to stop the threat
by the means of h6 or h5. If the pawn is on h6, it takes care of the g5 square
but Black won't be able to castle for some time, while on the h5 it can
potentially move even further, followed by Rh5.} h6 (9... h5 10. c4 Nc7 (10...
Nb4 11. Nc3 Nd3 12. e6 $1 {[%cal Gh4e4,Gf1d1] here this motif is even stronger
than with the black pawn on h6!}) 11. Nc3 Ne6 12. Re1 d6 13. exd6 (13. b3 {
here the same approach as after 9...h6 doesn't work as Black suddenly has an
unexpected resource h5-h4 in one of the lines.} dxe5 14. Nxe5 Qd4 $1 15. Qg3 $6
h4 $1 {[%cal Rh8h5]}) 13... Qxd6 14. Bd2 O-O 15. Ne4 Qc7 16. Bc3 f6 17. Rad1
$14 {[%emt 0:00:09] transforms to one of the lines as already suggested in
Chapter}) (9... O-O $6 {this is extremely dangerous for Black.} 10. c4 $1 {
it appears to be an accurate intermezzo before playing Bh6. The threat to play
Bh6 will be available also after 1-2 moves.} (10. Bh6 e6 11. Qh3 Ba6 12. Re1 f5
{and White's attack is over.}) 10... Nb4 (10... Nc7 11. Bh6 Ne6 12. Nc3 $16 {
Black is too passive}) 11. Nc3 Nd3 12. Bh6 Nxe5 (12... Nxb2 $4 13. Rab1 Nd3 14.
Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Qd4 $18) 13. Ng5 f6 14. Bxg7 fxg5 15. Qd4 Kxg7 16. Qxe5+ Kg8 17.
Qxg5 $16) 10. c4 Nc7 (10... Nb4 $6 {I have a feeling that the knight is
misplaced here.} 11. Nc3 {since the queen is on h4, White doesn't need to
worry about the Nc2 threat} Nd3 (11... c5 $6 12. a3 {[%cal Gh4e4,Ge4c2,Ge4a8]}
Nc6 13. Be3 $16) (11... d6 12. Rd1 $14) (11... Bb7 12. c5 $14) 12. e6 $1 {
[%cal Gh4e4,Ge4g6,Gf1d1] a very unpleasant surprise for Black! For example,} (
12. Be3 $5) (12. Qe4 $5) 12... f5 $6 (12... Qa5 $1 {quite impossible to find
this best move over the board} 13. Rd1 Qf5 14. Nd4 $1 Qe5 15. Qh3 $1 Nxc1 16.
exf7+ Kxf7 17. Raxc1 $14) 13. Be3 $1 Bf6 14. Qg3 g5 15. Qh3 dxe6 16. Rad1 e5
17. Ne1 e4 18. Nxd3 exd3 19. Bc5 $16) 11. Nc3 Ne6 12. Re1 d6 (12... d5 13. cxd5
cxd5 14. Be3 $14 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gf3d4]}) 13. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Ga1d1]} dxe5 14.
Nxe5 Qc7 (14... Qd4 $6 15. Qg3 $16 {since there is no h5-h4 threat.}) 15. Qg3
$14 {[%cal Gc1b2,Ga1d1]}) 7. O-O d6 {a logical attempt to bring into life the
light-squared bishop and semi-fix the center. However, if Black does this, he
is already commited to play either c6-c5 or e7-e5 in a very near future as
White now has a clear target and will rush with c2-c4-c5.} (7... Bg7 8. c4 Nh6
9. c5 (9. Bxh6 $5 {given the circumstances that Black has wasted a tempo for
Bg7, this looks interesting.} Bxh6 10. Rd1 O-O 11. c5 Rb8 12. b3 {I'm not sure
this is a good move.} Kh8 $2 (12... Ba6 $5) 13. Na3 Qa5 14. Nc4 Qb4 15. Ne1 Qb7
16. Rd3 Qc7 17. Rad1 $16 Bg7 18. Qe3 Rd8 19. Qd2 Rb5 20. b4 Rb8 21. Na5 Bf8 22.
a3 Kg7 23. Nf3 d6 24. Nd4 Re8 25. Ndxc6 Ra8 26. Rc1 $18 {1-0 (32) Firouzja,A 
(2521)-Lorparizangeneh,S (2485) Hamedan 2017}) 9... Nf7 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Rd1 {
transforms to the main line}) (7... Nh6 {a standard unorthodox development of
the black knight in typical setups} 8. c4 Nf7 9. Nc3 Bg7 (9... Qb6 10. Qd3 {
White is not interested to exchange queens. The black queen becomes a target
to win a few tempos.} Bg7 11. Rb1 d6 12. Be3 Qa6 13. b4 Bg4 14. b5 Qc8 15. Nd2
$14) 10. c5 O-O {[%cal Re7e5,Rf6f5]} 11. Rd1 {[%cal Gb2b5,Ga1b1] the only
reasonable game plan for White here seems to be pushing forward the b-pawn and
pressuring the d-file.} Rb8 (11... e5 12. Qc4 Qe7 (12... a5 13. Na4) 13. b4 a5
(13... Rd8 14. Be3 Bf8 15. Na4 {[%cal Gc4c2,Ga4b2,Gb2c4]}) 14. b5 cxb5 15. Qxb5
Qe6 16. Rb1) (11... f5 12. Qc4 fxe4 13. Nxe4 $14) 12. Qc4 Qa5 {[%cal Rb8b4]}
13. a3 Ba6 14. Qa2 {[%csl Rd7]} Qc7 15. b4 f5 16. Bb2 $14) (7... Qb6 8. Qd3 $1
{trading queens favors Black.} Nh6 9. c4 Nf7 10. Nc3 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gc1e3,Gc4c5,
Gb2b5] doesn't change much of White's strategy. In example,} d6 11. Rb1 f5 12.
Be3 Qc7 13. c5 $14) (7... d5 $2 {Black is terribly behind in development to
fight for the center. The follow-up e7-e5 is impossible.} 8. Nc3) 8. c4 c5 (
8... e5 {a very tempting move to fight for the center with future plans of
f6-f5 but now White's plan is very simple - fight for the d5 square with the
pawn push b2-b4-b5, or perhaps even c4-c5 at some moment might become possible.
} 9. Qd3 Nh6 10. Nc3 {[%cal Gb2b5]} Nf7 (10... a5 11. Bxh6 Bxh6 12. Rfd1 Bf8
13. c5 $14) 11. b4 Be7 12. b5 {[%csl Gd5]} Qc7 13. bxc6 Qxc6 14. Nd5 $14 {
[%cal Gc1a3,Gf1d1,Ga1c1,Gc4c5]}) (8... Qb6 {an attempt to stop c4-c5} 9. c5 $1
Qxc5 (9... dxc5 $6 10. Qc3 {[%cal Gc1e3]}) 10. Qxc5 dxc5 11. Be3 e5 12. Rc1 $14
{[%cal Gb1d2,Ge3c5] 1-0 (57) Manik,M (2391)-Najgebauer,S (2273) Slovakia 2015})
(8... Bg4 9. c5 Bxf3 10. gxf3 $14) (8... Bg7 9. c5 d5 $6 {[%cal Re7e5]} 10. Qa4
$1 Bd7 11. exd5 cxd5 12. c6 Bf5 13. Nd4 $16) 9. Qd3 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gf3h4,Gf2f5,
Rf6f5] since Black is planning an eventual f6-f5 push to open his bishops at
g7 and b7, a logical idea is to prevent it by f2-f4-f5, which also helps White
to secure the outpost on d5.} Nh6 10. Nc3 Nf7 11. Nh4 Bb7 12. f4 Bh6 13. f5 {
it's not mandatory to execute it right now but I'll just illustrate the
position.} Bxc1 14. Raxc1 g5 15. Nf3 {White knights are more flexible for
maneuvering than Black. At the right time a2-a3 and b2-b4 will need to be
played.}) (5... Ba6 $5 {by this clever order of the moves Black can hope to
equalize the game if he can pick up a novelty!} 6. dxc5 Qa5+ 7. Nbd2 (7. c3 $5
Qxc5 8. Be3 Qa5 (8... Qb5 $1 $146) 9. Nbd2 d6 10. b4 Qc7 11. c4 Bg7 12. Rc1 Nf6
13. O-O O-O $11 14. Re1 Ng4 15. Bd4 e5 16. Bc3 Rae8 17. h3 Nh6 18. Qb3 Kh8 19.
c5 dxc5 20. bxc5 f5 21. Nc4 $16 {1-0 (56) Bailet,P (2519)-Dourerassou,J (2414)
Lille 2015}) 7... Nf6 $1 $146 {an interesting novelty!} (7... Qxc5 8. c4 {
[%csl Ra6] is essentially what Black wants to avoid, and White - on the
contrary!}) 8. a3 (8. Rb1 $2 {now this typical move doesn't work} Nxe4 9. b4
Qxa2 $17 {the knight is not hanging because the rook on b1 is unprotected})
8... Qxc5 9. c4 {After analysis I came to the conclusion that this is a more
accurate move than 9.b4} (9. b4 Qb6 (9... Qc3 $4 10. Rb1 {[%cal Gc1b2]}) 10. c4
(10. Bb2 Bg7 11. Bd4 c5 $1 12. Bxc5 Qe6 13. Ng5 Qc6 14. Bd4 O-O $44) 10... d5
$1 (10... Bg7 11. O-O O-O (11... Nxe4 $4 12. Nxe4 Bxa1 13. Be3) (11... d5 $1
12. Bb2 (12. exd5 $2 Nxd5 $17) (12. e5 Ne4 13. c5 $13) 12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 Bxc4
14. Bxf6 (14. Bd4 Qd8 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nxf6+ exf6 17. Re1+ Kf8 18. Qc1 Bd5 19.
Qh6+ Kg8 20. Rac1 Qf8 21. Qxf8+ Kxf8 22. Nd4 a5 $11) 14... Bxf6 15. Nxf6+ exf6
16. Re1+ Be6 17. Qd4 Qxd4 18. Nxd4 a5 $1 $11) 12. Bb2 $14 {transforms to a
variation covered later. If White can get to this position, he is simply
better.}) 11. exd5 (11. Qc2 dxc4 $1 $11) 11... Bg7 12. Bb2 cxd5 (12... Ne4 $6
13. Nxe4 Bxb2 14. Ra2 Bg7 15. Nfd2 $16) 13. Qa4+ Kf8 14. O-O (14. b5 Ne4 $1 {
[%cal Rb6f2]} 15. Bxg7+ Kxg7 16. O-O Nxd2 17. Nxd2 Bb7 18. Rac1 a6 $11) 14...
dxc4 15. Bd4 Qb5 (15... Qb7 16. Rfe1 $14) 16. Qxb5 (16. Qc2 Qf5) 16... Bxb5 17.
a4 Bc6 18. Ne5 Bd5 19. Rac1 Bh6 20. Rfd1 (20. f4 $5 g5 21. f5 g4 $13) 20... Kg7
21. Nexc4 Rhd8 22. Ne3 Kg8 23. Bxf6 exf6 24. Nxd5 Rxd5 25. Nb3 {and White is
pushing for a slight edge in the endgame}) 9... Nxe4 $5 {leads to a
complicated struggle} (9... Bg7 10. O-O (10. Qa4 $5 Qb6 11. O-O {also looks
very interesting and needs to be studied much more thoroughly before giving a
final verdict to this line.}) 10... d5 $1 11. exd5 Bxc4 $1 12. Nxc4 Qxc4 13. d6
O-O $1 (13... Rd8 14. Re1 e6 15. Ne5 Qd5 16. Qc2 $14) 14. dxe7 Rfe8 15. Bg5
Rxe7 16. Rc1 {perhaps White can push something out of this position but
objectively it's a draw.}) (9... Bxc4 10. Qc2 d5 11. b3 Ng4 (11... dxe4 $2 12.
Ng1 $18) 12. Nxc4 dxc4 13. Bb2 c3 $1 14. O-O Bg7 15. Rac1 O-O 16. Bxc3 $1 Bxc3
(16... Qxa3 17. e5 $14) 17. Qxc3 Qxa3 18. Ra1 Qd6 19. e5 {[%csl Rg4]} Qc7 20.
h3 Nh6 21. g4 Rfd8 22. Rfc1 $14) (9... d5 10. exd5 Bxc4 11. Qc2 cxd5 12. b3 Ng4
13. Nxc4 (13. Rf1 $4 Ne3 $1) 13... dxc4 14. b4 {[%cal Gc2a4]} Qc6 15. Bb2 c3
16. Qxc3 {White looks slightly more comfortable.}) 10. Nxe4 Qxc4 11. Nfd2 Qd5
12. Qf3 Bg7 13. Nc3 $13) (5... Qb6 $5 6. dxc5 Qxc5 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 {[%cal
Ge4e5] should essentially transform to one of the lines, covered later, and
White has yet to play Nbd2 and could opt for something else instead. Otherwise}
d6 9. Nbd2 Nf6 10. Nb3 {[%cal Ge4e5] and so on}) 6. dxc5 $1 {Forces Black's
reply.} Qa5+ (6... Ba6 7. Nbd2 {transforms to the main lines}) (6... Nf6 $6 7.
e5 Ng4 8. O-O $1 {a standard sacrifice} (8. Nfd2 $5 {is a cute little trick
that might not even be necessary!} d6 (8... Nxe5 $4 9. f4) (8... f5 9. exf6
Nxf6 10. O-O O-O 11. Nc3 $14) 9. exd6 exd6 10. O-O O-O 11. h3 Nf6 12. cxd6 Qxd6
13. Nb3 $14) 8... Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Bxe5 10. Re1 Bg7 (10... d6 11. Bh6 $1 {[%csl
Re8]} Bxb2 12. Nd2 $40) 11. Qd6 (11. Bg5 f6 12. Be3 Rb8 13. b3 O-O 14. Nc3 $14)
11... Kf8 12. Qg3 Ba6 13. Nc3 Bc4 14. Qh4 Be6 15. Bh6 Bxh6 16. Qxh6+ Kg8 17.
Ne2 Qf8 18. Qd2 h6 19. Nd4 Kh7 20. Re3 Qg7 21. Rae1 $16 {1-0 (49) Van Foreest,
J (2640)-Piscopo,P (2389) Pardubice 2018}) 7. Nbd2 Qxc5 {the best move for
Black as it keeps several setups still available for him.} (7... Ba6 $6 {
[%cal Ra6f1] it's extremely tempting to keep the white king in the center and
the c5 pawn seemingly is going nowhere but this is where all Black's problems
start! Later Black will realize that the bishop on a6 is simply misplaced.} 8.
Rb1 $1 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc2c4] A nasty surprise! It's obvious that White now
intends to keep the c5 pawn by playing b2-b4 so Black has to choose whether to
take it, or perhaps the a2 pawn?} (8. a3 {not as strong as 8.Rb1} Qxc5 9. c4
Nf6 $6 (9... Bxc4 $1 10. Qc2 d5 $11 {[%csl Ra1][%cal Rb2b3]}) 10. b4 Qb6 11.
O-O O-O (11... d5 $11) 12. Bb2 d6 13. Qc2 Bc8 14. e5 Bf5 15. Qb3 dxe5 16. Bxe5
$11 {1-0 (35) Nepomniachtchi,I (2759)-Dubov,D (2703) Sochi 2018}) (8. c4 $2
Bxc4) 8... Qxa2 {a risky choice - Black now has to avoid a clever trap where
several good players have already fallen into!} (8... Rb8 9. a3 {doesn't
change much} Qxc5 10. b4 Qb6 11. c4 $14 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gc1b2,Ge1g1] 1-0 (70)
Nakar,E (2461)-Vorontsov,P (2578) Irving 2018}) (8... Qxc5 9. c4 $1 {[%cal
Gb2b4,Ge1g1,Gc1b2] it is entirely possible to start with 9.b4! as well, then
10.c4. White's plan is very simple - proceed with short castle, then Bb2 and
execute e4-e5.} Nf6 (9... Nh6 10. b4 Qd6 11. O-O O-O 12. h3 f5 13. e5 Qc7 14.
Re1 Bc8 15. Nb3 Nf7 16. Qe2 Rb8 17. a3 e6 18. h4 Re8 19. Bf4 Qd8 20. Rbd1 h6
21. Qe3 Kh7 22. Qxa7 {1-0 (43) Kovalev,V (2667)-Yedigaryan,A (1622) Moscow 2018
}) (9... Qa5 10. b4 $1 Qc7 (10... Qxa2 $6 11. Bb2 (11. Rb3 $5 Qa4 12. Qe2 $16 {
[%cal Ge1g1,Gc1b2]}) 11... Bxb2 12. Qc2) 11. Bb2 Bxb2 12. Rxb2 d6 13. O-O Nf6
14. Re1 O-O 15. e5 dxe5 16. Nxe5 $16 {1-0 (64) Neiksans,A (2568)-Rogule,L 
(2257) Olaine 2018}) (9... Bxc4 $4 10. Qc2 d5 11. b3) (9... Rb8 10. O-O {
[%cal Ga2a3,Gb2b4]}) (9... d5 $2 10. exd5 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gd1a4]}) 10. b4 Qb6
11. O-O {probably around here Black will realize that the Ba6 move was not so
good after all.} d6 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Bd4 $1 {a nice intermezzo move - the black
queen has no suitables squares to retreat not to lose another tempo.} Qc7 14.
e5 dxe5 15. Bxe5 Qc8 16. Qc2 c5 17. b5 Bb7 18. Rfe1 $14 {1-0 (33) Santos
Latasa,J (2546)-Luch,M (2396) Lisbon 2018}) 9. b4 {[%cal Gb1b3,Gb3a3,Gc2c4]}
Bc4 {pretty much the only move to stop Rb3} (9... Bb5 $2 10. Rb3 $16 f5 $4 {
Black falls into a typical trap for this line} (10... Ba4 $4 11. Ra3 Qxc2 12.
Rxa4) (10... Nf6 $4 11. Ra3 Qe6 12. c4 Nxe4 13. Qe2 Bc3 14. Rxc3 Nxc3 15. Qxe6
dxe6 16. Bb2 Ba4 17. Bxc3 $18 {1-0 (30) Banzea,A (2313)-Polyakov,F (2036)
Porto Carras 2018}) (10... h6 {almost the only move not to lose immediately
but it's not going to be pretty for Black.} 11. e5) 11. Ra3 Qe6 12. c4 $1 fxe4
13. Ng5 Qf5 14. Nh3 $18 {1-0 (21) Ortiz Suarez,I (2543)-Martinez Duany,L (2509)
Havana 2018}) (9... f5 $6 10. exf5 gxf5 (10... Qf7 11. Bb2 $16) 11. Rb3 $16 {
[%cal Gc2c4,Gb3a3]}) (9... Rb8 $4 10. Rb3 {the same trap} Bb5 11. Ra3 Qe6 12.
c4 $1 $18 {[%cal Gf3g5] 1-0 (17) Artemiev,V (2692)-Potapov,P (2479) St
Petersburg 2017}) (9... d5 10. cxd6 Rd8 11. Rb3 Bb5 12. e5 exd6 13. Ra3 Qe6 14.
Nd4 $16 {[%cal Ga3e3,Re8e3]}) 10. e5 $1 Nh6 {and now White has a pleasant
choice between two plans.} 11. Rb2 (11. Bb2 O-O 12. Qc1 Qa6 (12... Be6 $6 13.
Ra1 Qd5 14. c4 Qd3 15. Ra3 Qf5 16. O-O $16 f6 17. Nd4 Qh5 18. Nxe6 dxe6 19. Rh3
Qg4 20. Nb3 Nf5 21. Na5 Rac8 22. f3 Qg5 23. f4 Qg4 24. Qd1 Qxd1 25. Rxd1 {
1-0 (54) Harutjunyan,G (2470)-Buksa,N (2437) Vilnius 2018}) 13. Ra1 Qb5 14. Bc3
Bd5 15. Ra5 Qb8 16. Qb2 $14 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gf1a1]}) 11... Qa6 12. Nxc4 Qxc4 13.
Qe2 Qxe2+ 14. Kxe2 Ng4 15. Ra2 Nxe5 16. Bb2 f6 17. Nxe5 fxe5 18. Rha1 $14) (
7... Nf6 8. O-O Qxc5 9. Nb3 {transforms to a line covered later.}) 8. O-O {
and again, Black is at the crossroads. He needs to figure out how to develop
the knight on g8. If it goes to f6, should he play d6 first? White's play is
very straightforward - Re1 and e4-e5.} d6 {probably the most solid approach -
Black makes sure that e4-e5 push won't force his knight away from the f6
square, but then again allows White to open up the position.} (8... Nh6 {
this maneuver is much more flexible than Nf6 and Black doesn't need to
immediately react against e4-e5 but by doing this Black risks that the knight
will be cut-off from the action very quickly by the means of h2-h3.} 9. e5 Ng4
(9... O-O 10. Nb3 Qc4 11. h3 {[%csl Rh6]} a5 12. a4 c5 13. Bd2 $14) 10. Nb3 Qd5
(10... Qb6 11. Qe2 a5 12. h3 {transforms to a covered line, had Black played 8.
..Nf6}) 11. Bf4 Qxd1 12. Raxd1 f6 13. exf6 Nxf6 14. Rfe1 $14 O-O 15. Rxe7 Nd5
16. Rxg7+ Kxg7 17. Bd6 Re8 18. Nc5 a5 19. c4 Nb4 20. Be5+ Kf8 21. a3 Na6 22.
Ne4 $16 {1-0 (31) Safarli,E (2676)-Sulypa,O (2487) ECC 2018}) (8... Nf6 {
this allows White to start an immediate action with e4-e5.} 9. Nb3 (9. b3 $5
$146) 9... Qb6 (9... Qh5 10. Re1 {[%cal Ge4e5]} O-O (10... Ng4 {[%cal Rg4e5]}
11. Bf4 $1 Bxb2 12. h3 Nh6 (12... Nf6 $6 13. Rb1 Bc3 14. Re3 {[%csl Rc3]}) 13.
Rb1 Bc3 14. Re3 Bg7 15. e5 O-O 16. Qd3 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gg2g4]}) 11. e5 Ng4 12.
Bf4 f6 13. exf6 Rxf6 14. Bg3 Rf7 15. h3 Nh6 16. Be5 d6 17. Bxg7 Rxg7 18. Qd3
$14 (18. Re4 $6 {1-0 (37) Paravyan,D (2620)-Palachev,P (2402) Sochi 2018})) 10.
e5 Ng4 (10... Nd5 11. c4 Nc7 12. Be3 {doesn't look fun for Black.}) 11. Qe2 $1
$146 (11. Bf4 $6 {1-0 (55) Ochsner,B (2459)-Light,B (2234) Denmark 2017} Ba6)
11... a5 12. h3 Ba6 (12... a4 13. hxg4 axb3 14. Be3 $14) 13. c4 a4 14. hxg4 (
14. Nbd2 Nh6 15. Ne4 O-O 16. Rd1 Qb4) 14... axb3 15. axb3 c5 (15... Qxb3 $6 16.
Ra3 {[%cal Gf1a1]} Qb6 17. Be3 c5 18. b4 $1 $16) 16. Bg5 h5 17. Qe3 $1 (17. Bf6
$5) 17... hxg4 18. Nh2 $14) (8... d5 $146 {If Black attempts to fight for the
center, in White's best interest it's to close the center and execute c2-c4 to
either open the position at the queenside, or at least to secure a nice
outpost at d4.} 9. e5 {[%csl Rg7]} Qb6 (9... Bg4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 e6 12.
Be3 Qb5 13. a4 $14) 10. c4 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gd2b3,Gb3d4]}) 9. Re1 Nf6 (9... a5 $5
$146 {[%cal Ra5a4] a very interesting way to postpone the development of the
black knight and fight for a space advantage at the queenside. By doing this
Black probably is ready to sacrifice the a-pawn at some moment to fight for
the initiative.} 10. a4 {[%csl Ra5] a necessity otherwise the a-pawn will
continue to roll forward.} Nf6 (10... Be6 $5 {[%cal Re6b3]} 11. Nb3 (11. h3 $5
Nf6 12. e5 dxe5 13. Nxe5 O-O 14. Ndf3 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2,Gb2a3]}) 11... Bxb3
12. cxb3 Nf6 13. Be3 Qh5 14. Bd4 O-O 15. e5 dxe5 16. Nxe5) 11. e5 {with the
inclusion of a5 and a4, this is a more precise move order.} (11. Nb3 Qb6 12. e5
Ng4 $1 13. exd6 Qxf2+ 14. Kh1 Qa7 $1 {otherwise this square would not be
available} 15. Qe2 (15. Rxe7+ $4 Qxe7 16. dxe7 Nf2+) 15... Nf2+ 16. Kg1 Nh3+
17. Kh1 $11) 11... dxe5 (11... Ng4 $2 12. Ne4) 12. Nb3 Qd6 13. Nxe5 Nd5 14. Nc4
Qc7 15. Bd2 O-O 16. Nbxa5 $13 {Black obviously has some compensation for the
pawn but still - a pawn is a pawn!}) 10. Nb3 Qb6 11. e5 dxe5 (11... Ng4 $6 {
extremely tempting but objectively bad} 12. exd6 Qxf2+ 13. Kh1 Qb6 14. Rxe7+
Kf8 15. Re2 $16 {here tactics work in White's favor.}) 12. Nxe5 O-O 13. Bd2 {
[%cal Gc2c4,Gd2c3,Gc3a5,Gd1e2,Ge2f3] White's position looks slightly better
due to the good control of the squares and what is most important - he has no
weaknesses and can easily improve the placement of his pieces. Finally I would
like to add that I'm pretty sure that Black can improve his play somewhere
along the way, but the same can be said about White. A very well prepared
player probably will find a good setup for Black that he will find to be
perspective but overall I think this is a very decent setup to be tested in
the long term. The practice will show if I'm right or not.} (13. Be3 {1-0 (51)
Potapov,P (2479)-Smirnov,P (2576) Khanty-Mansiysk 2017}) *

