1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {You can only imagine my joy when I saw that the
two of the best players in the World championship match decided to go for the
Rossolimo - something I recently actually wrote a database for!} g6 4. Bxc6
dxc6 {As I mentioned in my Rossolimo database, with this continuation Black
aims for a peaceful position which includes a lot of maneuvering and
positional understanding - a perfect choice by the World Champion! While not
as popular as it's aggressive cousin 4...bxc6, the whole system has some
resemblence to a brick wall that White is trying to break through - and as it
happened, the challenger couldn't crack through. I can only imagine that after
the World Championship this system will become even more popular, and combined
together with the Sveshnikov variation, it will be a tough nut to crack!} 5. d3
Bg7 6. h3 {in the 3rd game of the match Caruana decided to go for 6.0-0
without h3.} Nf6 7. Nc3 Nd7 {[%cal Re7e5,Rd7f8,Rf8e6] One of the main moves
and motifs of the whole setup - Black aims for a quicker e7-e5 push, followed
by Nd7-f8-e6, at the same time postponing castling for the time being.} 8. Be3
e5 9. O-O b6 $5 {Black defends the c5 pawn and prepares his knight to maneuver
to d4. It is a logical but still a rare move but I assume it comes with a very
deep idea! In my database I mentioned only 9...Qe7 which is a much more
popular move. I'll present to you a comparison from the database and probably
what team Carlsen had improved.} (9... Qe7 10. Qd2 h6 11. Nh2 {this particular
line for Black is dangerous} Nf8 12. f4 exf4 13. Bxf4 Ne6 14. Bg3 $1 {[%cal
Ge4e5,Gc3e4] with ideas of e4-e5 and Nc3-e4. I'm sure Fabiano perfectly knows
this line.} Qg5 15. Qe1 {The following moves are almost forced} Nd4 16. Qf2 $1
{[%cal Gf2f7,Gg3h4]} O-O 17. Bd6 Bxh3 18. Bf4 Qxg2+ 19. Qxg2 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 {
and after a few moves in my analysis I concluded that White's chances are
better. Please note that the black pawn on c5 is undefended and for example,}
g5 {fails to} 21. Bd6 $16 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gd6f8,Gd6c5] Now let's check what
could have happened in the game.}) 10. Nh2 {Caruana decides to deviate from
the main move 10.Qd2 - perhaps he felt what's coming and thought that he has
to play f2-f4 either now or never before Black positions his knight to e6.
However, I think he should had at least checked if Carlsen really will play 10.
..h6 and then proceed in the manner that I was describing in the database,
although in a different variation.} (10. Qd2 h6 $1 (10... Nf8 $5 {is also
possible but less clear} 11. Bh6 (11. Ne2 Ne6 12. Nh2 {probably is also
interesting, preparing f2-f4 at the right time.}) 11... Qf6 {usually the black
queen stands on e7 so that for this occasion he could continue with f7-f6.
Although the queen seems to be misplaced on f6, White can't immediately take
advantage of it.} 12. a4 a5 13. Ne2 Ne6 14. Nh2 Bxh6 ({or the more aggressive} 
14... g5 $5 15. Ng4 Qg6 16. Bxg7 Qxg7 17. Ne3 Nf4 18. Nc4 Rb8 19. Ng3 {with a
symbolic plus for White}) 15. Qxh6 Qg5 16. Qxg5 Nxg5 17. f4 exf4 18. Nxf4 {
White looks slightly better}) 11. Nh2 Nf8 12. f4 (12. Ne2 $5 {my suggested
game plan} Ne6 13. Rae1 {[%cal Gb2b3,Ga2a4] in comparison to what I analyzed
in the database, here White doesn't get to exchange the dark-squared bishops
but at the same time the Black king is stuck in the center. White can first
fix the pawns at the queenside with b2-b3 and a2-a4 and the proceed with f2-f4.
I don't know how the game could had proceeded, but here's a possible idea.} a5
(13... g5 $5 {[%csl Gf4,Rf5] perhaps Black should go for this maneuver sooner
or later? This would stop the f2-f4 thrust for good but at the same time it
would lead to a very double-edged game. I don't think this is an easy decision
for Black to make as it seriously weakens the f5 square.}) 14. a4 Ra7 15. b3
Re7 16. f4 exf4 17. Nxf4 Nxf4 18. Bxf4 Be6 19. Kh1 $14 {and White's position
seems to be better because of a simple attack at the kingside, and Black lacks
a clear game plan.}) 12... exf4 13. Bxf4 Ne6 14. Bg3 {I assume Fabiano typical
idea because of the following move} Qg5 $1 $146 15. Qe1 Nd4 16. Qf2 O-O {
and now the whole plan of} 17. Bd6 Bxh3 18. Bf4 Qxg2+ 19. Qxg2 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 {
is not so great because of a sudden new resource} g5 $1 {[%csl Gc5] and the c5
pawn is protected!} 21. Bd2 Nxc2 22. Rad1 Rad8 {and only Black can be better.})
10... Nf8 11. f4 $146 {unbelievable but it's a technical novelty! Of course,
the idea is typical.} exf4 12. Rxf4 {Although a standard but still a slightly
disappointing choice. It would be interesting to see what Carlsen would do
after} (12. Bxf4 Ne6 13. Bg3 $5 Nd4 {[%cal Rc8e6]} 14. Qd2 {[%cal Ga1e1,Ge4e5,
Gh2g4] and at least White has a clear game plan.}) 12... Be6 $1 {a very
powerful idea which is revealed in the next two moves.} 13. Rf2 h6 $1 {[%cal
Rg6g5,Rf8g6] it appears that the black knight is not even heading to d4 but to
g6!} 14. Qd2 {I don't understand this move - since Black is certainly going to
play g6-g5, the battery of the queen and the bishop won't work, so why put the
queen there? I think White should have been more alert that the typical plan
here won't work and think of something else while it's not too late. Since the
black knight isn't going to e6-d4 but g6, perhaps it would make sense to
prepare d3-d4? I would think about including a2-a4 first, threatening a4-a5
and trying to provoke a7-a5 as a reply. Then Qe2, Rd1, Nf3 and d3-d4 at least
looks as a solid game plan, and in case Black is thinking about long castling,
the queen from e2 can directly jump to a6.} g5 15. Raf1 {a yet another
automatic decision to double the rooks while it's actual value is not clear.
If White would start with 15.a4! it would remind Black that castling long can
have consequences.} (15. a4 $1) 15... Qd6 $1 {[%cal Rf8g6,Rg6e5,Re8c8] Magnus
is taking over the initiative and at this critical moment Fabiano completely
lost control of the game. It was not too late to include a2-a4 and bring back
the knight from h2 to life. Obviously, White is fighting for the equality now.}
16. Ng4 $6 (16. a4 a5 17. Nf3 O-O-O 18. Qe2 Kb7 19. d4 $11 {[%cal Gf1d1] White
is too solid to be worse}) 16... O-O-O 17. Nf6 Nd7 18. Nh5 {[%cal Gh2g4,Gg4f6,
Gf6h5] this weird journey of the knight can hardly be called as a success!} Be5
19. g4 f6 $17 {the rest I won't comment - I'm surprised Carlsen didn't convert
this game to a win.} 20. b3 Bf7 21. Nd1 Nf8 22. Nxf6 Ne6 23. Nh5 Bxh5 24. gxh5
Nf4 25. Bxf4 gxf4 26. Rg2 Rhg8 27. Qe2 Rxg2+ 28. Qxg2 Qe6 29. Nf2 Rg8 30. Ng4
Qe8 31. Qf3 Qxh5 32. Kf2 Bc7 33. Ke2 Qg5 34. Nh2 h5 (34... Qe5 $19 {[%cal
Re5b2]}) 35. Rf2 Qg1 (35... Qg7 $19 {[%cal Rg7b2]}) 36. Nf1 h4 (36... Qg7 $19 {
[%cal Rg7b2]}) 37. Kd2 Kb7 38. c3 Be5 (38... Rg3 $1 39. Nxg3 hxg3 40. Re2 Qa1
$19) 39. Kc2 Qg7 $4 {the last mistake - after this White escapes with a draw} (
39... b5 $19) 40. Nh2 $1 Bxc3 41. Qxf4 Bd4 42. Qf7+ Ka6 43. Qxg7 Rxg7 44. Re2
Rg3 45. Ng4 Rxh3 46. e5 Rf3 47. e6 Rf8 48. e7 Re8 49. Nh6 h3 50. Nf5 Bf6 51. a3
b5 52. b4 cxb4 53. axb4 Bxe7 54. Nxe7 h2 55. Rxh2 Rxe7 $15 56. Rh6 Kb6 57. Kc3
Rd7 58. Rg6 Kc7 59. Rh6 Rd6 60. Rh8 Rg6 61. Ra8 Kb7 62. Rh8 Rg5 63. Rh7+ Kb6
64. Rh6 Rg1 65. Kc2 Rf1 66. Rg6 Rh1 67. Rf6 Rh8 68. Kc3 Ra8 69. d4 Rd8 70. Rh6
Rd7 71. Rg6 Kc7 72. Rg5 Rd6 73. Rg8 Rh6 74. Ra8 Rh3+ 75. Kc2 Ra3 76. Kb2 Ra4
77. Kc3 a6 78. Rh8 Ra3+ 79. Kb2 Rg3 80. Kc2 Rg5 81. Rh6 Rd5 82. Kc3 Rd6 83. Rh8
Rg6 84. Kc2 Kb7 85. Kc3 Rg3+ 86. Kc2 Rg1 87. Rh5 Rg2+ 88. Kc3 Rg3+ 89. Kc2 Rg4
90. Kc3 Kb6 91. Rh6 Rg5 92. Rf6 Rh5 93. Rg6 Rh3+ 94. Kc2 Rh5 95. Kc3 Rd5 96.
Rh6 Kc7 97. Rh7+ Rd7 98. Rh5 Rd6 99. Rh8 Rg6 100. Rf8 Rg3+ 101. Kc2 Ra3 102.
Rf7+ Kd6 103. Ra7 Kd5 104. Kb2 Rd3 105. Rxa6 Rxd4 106. Kb3 Re4 107. Kc3 Rc4+
108. Kb3 Kd4 109. Rb6 Kd3 110. Ra6 Rc2 111. Rb6 Rc3+ 112. Kb2 Rc4 113. Kb3 Kd4
114. Ra6 Kd5 115. Ra8 1/2-1/2

