{After the first game many experts thought that the Rossolimo made it's only
appearance in the match and that starting with the 3rd game Caruana will
switch to a more active approach. On the contrary, I was quite sure we will
see a few more Rossolimo's as nobody prepares a whole setup for just one game,
especially in a World Championship match.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {the
second game the challenger gets to play White and the second Rossolimo! This
only means that Fabiano truly believes in the Rossolimo system.} g6 4. Bxc6
dxc6 {no surprises so far - Black has several setups he can choose from so he
shouldn't be too afraid if White managed to prepare something deadly in 3 days
since the first game.} 5. d3 Bg7 6. O-O {the first surprise! Usually here
White includes h2-h3 and thus doesn't allow Black to play Bg4. I've always
wondered - is h3 really such an important addition for this line for White? It
probably is - if Bg4 is not an immediate problem, it could become later and
most likely h3 will be needed anyway.} Qc7 $5 {The World champion responds
with a very interesting counter-surprise with an attempt to steer away from
known theoretical paths. Black is waiting for White to define his setup and
can postpone making any decisions by including b7-b6 as well. In my analysis
I'll try to explain what the Carlsen team might had prepared.} (6... Bg4 7.
Nbd2 Nf6 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Nxf3 Nd7 {is a similar position with the only
difference that Black has traded his c8 bishop for White's queenside knight.
Black remains very solid with the same approach - e7-e5 and reroute the knight
to e6. Black loses some dynamics because of the loss of the two bishop
advantage.}) 7. Re1 {It's not what I would play here - the rook in this setup
is rarely well placed on e1 and Bg4 will be a threat to think about at any
given time later. At least White forces Black to play e7-e5 immediately so
that he can pursue the a2-a3 and b2-b4 plan.} (7. h3 $1 {My suggestion is to
stick to the known values!} e5 (7... Nf6 $6 {This would be too early} 8. e5 $1
({and not} 8. Nc3 e5 9. Be3 b6 10. Qd2 O-O 11. Nh2 Nh5 $1 {probably would be
what Black would want to achieve}) 8... Nd5 (8... Nd7 $6 9. e6 $1 fxe6 10. Nbd2
{[%cal Gf1e1,Gd1e2,Gd2c4] and White's strategy is like a walk in the park -
Black has a really unpleasant position.}) 9. c4 {and the black knight has no
access to the c7 square anymore!} Nb4 10. a3 Na6 11. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Gb1c3,
Gc1f4] White has a better position and Qc7 is not helping for the a6 knight to
get back into game. Probably this is not what Magnus had in his mind.}) (7...
b6 $5 {would be a tricky way for Black to wait for White to define his setup
and most likely this is what Carlsen had in his mind for the particular game
but then again - b7-b6 might be a waste of time as White did not play Be3.
These positions can be really tricky! The good news for White is that he can
always choose between the Nf3-h2 and f2-f4 setup, or aim for the a2-a3 and
b2-b4 (if Black has played e7-e5).} 8. Nc3 (8. e5 $5 $146 {taking into account
that Black is so much behind in development, it would make sense to open the
position, even if it requires a pawn sacrifice. However, if White is not ready
for this line and especially in a World championship match it's not an easy
choice to sacrifice a pawn for an initiative that might fizzle out several
moves later.} Bxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Nc3 $13 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gf1e1,Gd1f3,Gc1f4]
}) ({also interesting would be} 8. Nbd2 $5 Nf6 (8... e5 9. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4]
and White switches to the alternate plan, although the bishop is not on e3.})
9. e5 Nd5 10. Re1 {and so on.}) 8... Nf6 $1 (8... e5 9. Nh2 Ne7 10. f4 O-O 11.
fxe5 Bxe5 12. Nf3 Bg7 13. Qe1 f5 14. Qh4 fxe4 15. dxe4 {[%cal Gc1h6,Gf3g5]
doesn't feel like an equality for Black to me.}) 9. e5 {the only way for White
to fight for anything - White can't allow Black to play e7-e5 and Nh5.} (9. Nh2
$6 Nh5 $1 {[%cal Re7e5] and now f2-f4 fails to Bd4+ and White suddenly loses.
Black plays e7-e5 just in time and get a very good game.}) 9... Nd5 {and now
yet again White has the opportunity to sacrifice the pawn for an initiative,
or play it safe.} 10. Ne4 $1 (10. Re1 Nxc3 11. bxc3 c4 $1 $11) 10... Bxe5 11.
Nxe5 Qxe5 12. Re1 {[%cal Gc2c4,Gc1d2]} O-O 13. Nxc5 {and White's position
still feels more pleasant because Black has a weakened king.}) 8. Be3 $1 {
an important order of the moves! White provokes b7-b6 so that after the
eventual a2-a3 and b2-b4, Black can't immediately equalize with cxb4 and a7-a5.
} ({if} 8. a3 Nf6 9. Be3 c4 $1 {becomes an option}) 8... b6 9. a3 {and it's
not easy for Black to meet the b2-b4 threat. In example,} Nf6 (9... a5 {
is a bit risky because White can prepare the b2-b4 breakthrough} 10. Nbd2 Ne7
11. Nc4 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gb2b4]} a4 12. b3 Ba6 13. Nfd2 Nc8 (13... axb3 14. a4
$1 bxc2 (14... Nd5 $5) 15. Qxc2 $14 {[%cal Ga4a5,Gf1b1]}) 14. bxa4 Bxc4 15.
Nxc4 Rxa4 16. Qb1 O-O 17. Qb3 Ra6 18. Rfb1 Re8 19. a4 Qa7 20. Ra3 Bf8 21. Qb2
Rxa4 22. Rxa4 Qxa4 23. Ra1 {1-0 (52) Gadimbayli,A (2420)-Savanovic,V (2294)
Paracin 2018}) 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. b4 Nd7 (11... cxb4 12. axb4 $14 {[%cal Gd1b1,
Gb1b2]}) 12. bxc5 Nxc5 13. Bxc5 bxc5 14. Qe1 $14 {[%cal Gd2b3,Ge1c3]}) 7... e5
{of course} 8. a3 Nf6 9. b4 O-O $1 {A typical pawn sacrifice - the pawn on c5
supposedly isn't going anywhere.} 10. Nbd2 Bg4 {it was not mandatory to give
up the bishop but at least it clarifies the situation a bit for Black.} (10...
cxb4 11. axb4 Be6 12. Bb2 Nh5 13. Ra3 a6 14. Qa1 f6 15. d4 exd4 16. Nxd4 Bf7 {
Black looks very solid although White is pressing.}) 11. h3 (11. bxc5 {
accepting the challenge should be a decent alternative} Nd7 12. a4 Nxc5 13. Ba3
b6 14. h3 Be6 15. Nb3 Bxb3 (15... Nxb3 16. Bxf8 Nxa1 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Qxa1 f6
19. d4 $14) 16. cxb3 Rfd8 17. Bxc5 bxc5 18. Rc1 Bf8 19. Rc3 {is slightly
unpleasant for Black}) 11... Bxf3 12. Nxf3 cxb4 13. axb4 a5 14. bxa5 Rxa5 15.
Bd2 $6 {after the game in the press conference Caruana described this as a
blackout - he thought that it leads to the same position as mentioned in the
sideline but in reality he simply missed Carlsen's next move!} (15. Rxa5 Qxa5
16. Bd2 Qc7 17. Qa1 Nd7 18. Qa7 Rb8 19. Rb1 $14) 15... Raa8 $1 {Black keeps
control of the a-file and White's little advantage eventually fizzles out.} 16.
Qb1 Nd7 17. Qb4 Rfe8 18. Bc3 b5 $11 19. Rxa8 Rxa8 20. Ra1 Rxa1+ 21. Bxa1 Qa7
22. Bc3 Qa2 23. Qb2 Qxb2 24. Bxb2 f6 25. Kf1 Kf7 26. Ke2 Nc5 {The World
champion tried to push a little in the endgame but White is too solid thus a
draw is inevitable.} 27. Bc3 Ne6 28. g3 Bf8 29. Nd2 Ng5 30. h4 Ne6 31. Nb3 h5
32. Bd2 Bd6 33. c3 c5 34. Be3 Ke7 35. Kd1 Kd7 36. Kc2 f5 37. Kd1 fxe4 38. dxe4
c4 39. Nd2 Nc5 40. Bxc5 Bxc5 41. Ke2 Kc6 42. Nf1 b4 43. cxb4 Bxb4 44. Ne3 Kc5
45. f4 $1 {clearly Fabiano already saw that Black's h-pawn has the wrong
corner for the bishop!} exf4 46. gxf4 Ba5 47. f5 gxf5 48. Nxc4 Kxc4 49. exf5 {
[%csl Ra5,Rh5][%cal Ge2f3,Gf3h1]} 1/2-1/2

