1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {The third game with White for Caruana brings the question
- will the challenger stick to his favorite Rossolimo or is he going to test
Carlsen's Sveshnikov? Many experts speculated that this is what the champion
had prepared against 3.d4 (and later it turned out to be true)} 3. Bb5 $1 {
Not yet! Fabiano gives the Rossolimo one more final chance to prove it's
power! For that I can only thank him.} g6 4. O-O {The first deviation -
usually it signals that White is not going to take on c6 and will go for an
alternate setup.} Bg7 5. Re1 {I didn't analyze this system in my Rossolimo
database but it's definitely a good alternative and with a much greater
history than Bxc6.} (5. c3 Nf6 6. Re1 O-O 7. h3 {[%cal Gd2d4] is a yet another
possible setup, supposedly harmless for Black.}) 5... e5 {[%cal Rg8e7,Rd7d6,
Re8g8] one of the main and thus the best moves - Black intends to play Nge7,
0-0, d7-d6 and f7-f5. It actually suits Carlsen's style very much so team
Caruana should have expected it.} (5... Nf6 {is a possible alternative} 6. e5
Nd5 7. Nc3 Nc7 8. Bxc6 dxc6 9. Ne4 {would be a typical approach - here Black
can choose between the modest 9...Ne6 and the more aggressive 9...b6 which
allows the 10.Nf6+ but gives Black the opportunity to play Bg4.} Ne6 (9... b6
10. Nf6+ Kf8 11. Ne4 Bg4 12. d3 Bxe5 $5 {not mandatory but tested several
times in a high level GM games. It's supposed to be a draw, but one mistake
can lead to a loss.} (12... Ne6 13. Ned2 Bh6 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Nxf3 Bxc1 16. Qxc1
Kg7 17. Re4 Qd5 18. b3 Rad8 19. Qa3 a5 20. Rae1 b5 21. Qc1 Nd4 22. Nxd4 cxd4
23. Qg5 Qe6 24. f4 {1-0 (48) Ye,J (2671)-Ni,H (2528) Hebei 2001}) 13. Nxe5 Bxd1
14. Bh6+ Kg8 15. Nxc6 Bxc2 16. Nxc5 $5 {this is the latest word in the line}
bxc5 17. Nxd8 Rxd8 18. Rxe7 Ne6 19. Re1 Ba4 20. Rxa7 Bc6 21. h4 Ra8 22. Rxe6
fxe6 23. Rc7 Rd8 24. Rxc6 Kf7 25. Rc7+ Ke8 26. Bg5 Rb8 27. Re7+ Kf8 28. Bf6 Ra8
29. a3 h5 30. Rc7 Rg8 31. f4 {1-0 (58) Mamedov,R (2678)-Dubov,D (2677)
Heraklio 2017}) 10. d3 b6 11. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge3h6]}) 6. b4 $5 {White plays
an interesting gambit! Perhaps Caruana just wanted to check if Carlsen had
properly done his homework and play a risk-free game? This eccentric idea has
been played before many times and certainly Carlsen with his team paid to it
some attention during their preparation.} (6. Bxc6 dxc6 {would be pretty much
the same what Caruana already played last game. White yet again has chosen Re1
whose contribution to the setup can be questioned and Black can choose between
Qc7 and Qe7. No surprise the challenger didn't want to go this way. The most
played continuation after} 7. d3 Qe7 8. Nbd2 Nf6 9. Nc4 Nd7 10. a4 O-O 11. a5
Rd8 12. Bd2 Nf8 {is quite fine for Black.} 13. Rb1 f6 14. b4 Be6 15. Ne3 b6 16.
axb6 axb6 17. bxc5 {1/2-1/2 (17) Anand,V (2766)-Leko,P (2722) Monte Carlo 2004}
) (6. a3 $5 Nge7 7. b4 d6 (7... cxb4 8. axb4 Nxb4 $2 9. Ba3 Nbc6 10. Bd6 O-O
11. Nc3 b6 12. Nd5 $16 {1-0 (54) Balog,I (2559)-Vovk,A (2624) Hungary 2018}) 8.
c3 O-O 9. d3 h6 10. Nbd2 Be6 11. Bb2 Rc8 12. Bc4 {1/2-1/2 (50) Rozentalis,E 
(2522)-Vuckovic,B (2588) Porto Carras 2018}) (6. Nc3 $5 Nge7 7. d3 O-O 8. Bc4
h6 9. a3 d6 10. Bd2 {[%cal Gb2b4]}) 6... Nxb4 $1 {the most accurate reply} (
6... cxb4 {is less clear but probably playable as well} 7. a3 b3 {a standard
way to decline a gambit} 8. cxb3 Nge7 9. Bb2 O-O 10. d4 $1 (10. b4 $6 a6 11.
Ba4 d5 12. exd5 Qxd5 13. Nc3 Qd3 14. Ne4 b6 15. Rc1 Bb7 16. Qe2 Qd5 17. Qe3 Qd8
18. Qg5 f6 19. Qe3 Kh8 20. Qe2 Rc8 21. Bb3 Nd5 22. d4 Nxd4 23. Nxd4 Rxc1 24.
Rxc1 exd4 25. Qd2 {0-1 (48) Bacrot,E (2708)-Grischuk,A (2761) Paris 2017})
10... exd4 11. Nxd4 $14) 7. Bb2 ({I was hoping for a continuation of the
gambit party!} 7. c3 $5 Nc6 8. d4 exd4 (8... cxd4 9. cxd4 exd4 10. Bf4 $146
Nge7 11. Bd6 $13 {also looks very interesting and worth to try!}) 9. e5 Nge7
10. Ba3 $13 {leads to some crazy lines - perhaps too wild for a World
championship match? I'm sure Magnus had a solid answer against these lines as
well, so Fabiano went for a safer choice.}) 7... a6 {Carlsen must had been
still within his home preparation.} 8. a3 {otherwise the knight will retreat
to c6 and White is down a pawn for no compensation. The gambit excitement
quickly fizzles out and the party is over.} axb5 9. axb4 Rxa1 10. Bxa1 d6 {
the e5 pawn is too important thus Black obviously defends it at all costs.} 11.
bxc5 Ne7 {very accurate, and all of this has already been played before,
although at an amateur level.} 12. Qe2 $146 {a novelty} (12. cxd6 Qxd6 13. d4
exd4 14. Bxd4 O-O 15. Nc3 Bxd4 16. Nxd4 b4 17. e5 Qc5 $11 {0-1 (46) Polschikov,
A (2270)-Anoshkin,A (2386) Pardubice 2007}) 12... b4 13. Qc4 {I can only
assume that Caruana was following his home preparation and hoping that Carlsen
won't find the not obvious strongest move! At that level it's the only way to
beat a super-GM, not to mention a World champion.} (13. Qb5+ Nc6 14. cxd6 Qxd6
15. d3 O-O 16. Nbd2 Be6 17. Nc4 Bxc4 18. Qxc4 Rc8 $11) 13... Qa5 $1 {very
accurate and extremely powerful!} (13... Qc7 {would be a typical human choice
and most likely what Fabiano was hoping for.} 14. Qxb4 dxc5 15. Qa4+ Bd7 16.
Qa8+ Nc8 17. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5,Ge1b1] and Black is facing some real problems.})
14. cxd6 Be6 $1 {an important intermezzo} 15. Qc7 Qxc7 16. dxc7 Nc6 17. c3 $6 {
A not so obvious inaccuracy - several times in the match the challenger kept
missing intermezzo moves, the last time was in the time trouble of the first
tiebreak game. Now despite the fact that White keeps his extra pawn, he has to
be very careful not to fall into trouble.} (17. Rd1 {was more challenging} Kd7
(17... Ke7 18. d4 Ra8 19. d5 Rxa1 20. dxe6 Ra8 21. exf7 Rc8 $14 {maybe is a
safer choice for Black but White definitely keep a solid plus.}) 18. d4 Bg4 $1
19. d5 Nd4 20. Nbd2 {but from afar it might not be easy to give a proper
evaluation of the position. Certainly White doesn't want to go to a position
and then discover that he's actually worse. Thus one of my rules is - if you
can't evaluate it, don't go there and choose something you understand.}) 17...
Kd7 (17... b3 $2 18. d4 $16) 18. cxb4 (18. d4 {[%cal Ga1h8] doesn't work
because of the pin} exd4 19. cxd4 Ra8 20. Nbd2 Kxc7 $17 {[%cal Rb4b2,Ra8a2]})
18... Ra8 $1 {a very important resource and most likely what Fabiano missed.
Now the bishop is forced to go to the awkward c3 square, leaving the knight
stranded on b1.} (18... Kxc7 19. Rc1 Kd7 20. Na3 Ra8 21. Nc2 {and perhaps
White is pushing for something although Black's piece activity should
guarantee him at least a draw.}) 19. Bc3 Kxc7 20. d3 Kb6 $6 {an uncommon
positional mistake by the World champion} (20... b5 $1 $15 {and White's
position is rather unpleasant as it's quite apparent that the b4 pawn will
fall, and Black is more active.} 21. Nbd2 $6 Rd8) 21. Bd2 {Caruana saves the
game in an elegant fashion by sacrificing two pawns in a row!} Rd8 22. Be3+ Kb5
23. Nc3+ $1 Kxb4 24. Nd5+ $1 Bxd5 25. exd5 Rxd5 26. Rb1+ Kc3 27. Rxb7 Nd8 28.
Rc7+ Kxd3 29. Kf1 {[%cal Gf3e1,Gg2g4,Gf1e2,Gf2f3] all forced - despite the
fact that Black has an extra pawn, White has too active pieces and actually
has even some funny checkmate ideas!} h5 30. h3 Ke4 {of course, Magnus is not
interested to find out what they are and simply gives up the pawn which means
an inevitable draw.} 31. Ng5+ Kf5 32. Nxf7 Nxf7 33. Rxf7+ Bf6 34. g4+ 1/2-1/2

