{[%cal Rb7b6,Rc6c5,Rc8b7,Re6e5,Gf2f4,Gf4f5,Ge4e5,Gc4f7] In the Rossolimo
database this pawn structure exclusively appears in the Chapter 6 with the
following order of the moves: 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 e6 4.0-0 Nge7 5.d4 cxd4
6.Nxd4 Qb6 7.Nxc6 dxc6.8.Bc4. While the pawn structure is symmetrical, it
doesn't mean the position it's drawish or equal - all that matters is the
piece activity and what you do about it. For a better understanding of the position, I left both light-squared bishops on the board. Before I
describe what to do for White, you need to understand Black's main motives: 1)
Black would love to play 1...e5 to fix the centre and open the bishop on c8.
If he can execute it without suffering an immediate punishment, it is a very
logical choice. The biggest drawback of such a decision is that by doing this
Black increases the power of the white bishop at c4 and the pin of the f7-pawn
might be unpleasant. Also Black could experience some problems to position the
bishop at a good square. The d7 square doesn't look appealing, after playing
Be6 Black ruins his pawn structure and the g4 square might not even be
available because of various reasons. Ideally if Black could manage to play
Be6 by not doubling the pawns or suffering something immediate, he would
equalize the game. Thus in White's best interest is not to allow it, as
described in Chapter 6 of the Rossolimo database. 2) Black can play either
b7-b5 or b7-b6, followed by Bb7 and finally c6-c5. By doing this he doesn't
increase the power of the white bishop and himself targets the e4 pawn.
However, this gives White free hands to start a kingside assault with f2-f4 
(assuming Black has short castled!). If Black has forced White to play e4-e5,
then the bishop from c4 can be repositioned to d3 where with a combined power
of the manoeuvres Rf1-f3-h3 and Qd1-h5 White can start a very powerful attack
against the Black king, targeting the h7 pawn. If the white pawn is still on
e4, then another option becomes viable once the dark bishop leaves the h3-c8
diagonal - meaning, f4-f5.}  *

