1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 {one of the main approaches against the
Rossolimo, but 3...g6 is more popular, also at the elite level.} 4. O-O Nge7 5.
d4 {currently the most topical move, although there are other approaches as
well.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 Qb6 {the most challenging move, otherwise White will just
step back with the bishop to e2 and setup the Maroczy Bind with c2-c4 and Nc3.}
7. Nxc6 dxc6 {Black aims for a symmetrical position and fights for a draw.} (
7... bxc6 {is another direction and a more aggressive approach} 8. Bd3 {
[%cal Gc2c4]}) (7... Qxb5 {is just bad because of} 8. Nd4 Qb6 9. Nc3 {[%cal
Ga4a5,Ga2a5,Gd4b3,Gc1e3,Gc3a4]}) 8. Bc4 $1 {a beautiful move with a deep
understanding of the position - White is thinking about a possible attack
after eventual f2-f4-f5 and for that, the bishop is placed perfectly on c4. If
Black tries to stop it and plays e6-e5, there will be an unpleasant pressure
to the f7 pawn.} Ng6 9. Kh1 $1 $146 {[%cal Gf2f4] at the time - a novelty!
White goes for a quick f2-f4.} Qc7 {since the black queen has nothing to do on
b6, it retreats to c7, preparing Bd6 manoeuvre.} (9... e5 {would stop White's
plan but give a green light to another} 10. Qf3 Qc7 11. Rd1 $1 {[%cal Gc4f7,
Gd1d8] and the threat of Bxf7 and Rd8+ is not easy to parry!} Nf4 12. Bxf4 exf4
13. e5 $1 Qxe5 14. Qb3 {and White has a dangerous initiative.}) 10. f4 Bd6 {
Clearly with an idea to provoke e4-e5 so that the f4-f5 threat is not so
dangerous. However, that's not the only plan White can choose.} 11. e5 Be7 12.
Nc3 O-O 13. Bd3 $1 {Since f4-f5 threat at the time being is not really
possible, White relocates the bishop to a more active square and can
immediately start an assault at the kingside.} b6 (13... c5 14. Rf3 Rd8 15. Rh3
c4 16. Qh5 cxd3 $4 17. Qxh7+ Kf8 18. Qh8+ Nxh8 19. Rxh8#) ({perhaps} 13... Nh4
{was better, trying to relocate the knight to f5, and after g7-g6 even to g7
but anyway Black is clearly worse.}) 14. a4 $6 {White goes in a wrong
direction and loses most of his advantage - in a classic game Caruana would
never miss the strongest continuation here.} (14. Qh5 $1 {[%cal Gf1f3,Gf3h3]}
c5 (14... Bb7 15. Rf3 Rad8 16. Rh3 h6 17. Be3 {[%cal Gf4f5]} Rxd3 18. cxd3 {
doesn't look fun for Black as well.}) 15. Rf3 c4 16. Be4 Bb7 17. Rh3 h6 18.
Bxb7 Qxb7 19. f5 exf5 20. Bxh6 gxh6 21. Qxh6 {with a devastating attack.})
14... a6 (14... c5 {was more accurate to stop the White's previously mentioned
attack.}) 15. Be4 Bb7 16. Be3 c5 17. g3 $14 {White has a little positional
edge because of the misplaced black knight on g6 but not much more.} f5 {
a big decision - Black deliberately ruins his pawn structure to gain some
space and bring back the knight.} (17... Rfd8 18. Qf3 Bxe4 19. Nxe4
Bf8 {[%cal Rg6e7,Re7d5] eventually should hold.}) 18. exf6 Bxf6 19. Qf3 Bxe4
20. Qxe4 Bxc3 21. bxc3 Rae8 22. Rad1 $14 {White has a little positional
advantage because he can target Black's weaknesses and Black can't respond
with the same but normally such a position is not possible to convert to a win
if the opponent defends accurately.} Re7 23. Rf2 {[%cal Gf2d2,Gd2d6]} Rd8 24.
Rxd8+ Qxd8 25. Rd2 Qc7 {a few inaccuracies have cost Black a pawn but despite
that he still has excellent drawing chances and White's queenside pawns are
weak.} 26. Qa8+ Kf7 27. Qxa6 Qb7+ 28. Qxb7 Rxb7 29. a5 bxa5 30. Bxc5 Ne7 31.
Rd8 Nd5 $6 {Black errs in the wrong moment - now his position becomes
difficult.} (31... Rc7 $1 32. Bd6 (32. Bd4 Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d8,Rc6d4]}) 32... Ra7
33. Kg1 a4 34. Ba3 Rc7 35. c4 Nf5 36. c5 Ne3 37. c3 Nc2 38. Bb4 Ra7 39. c6 a3
40. Rd7+ Rxd7 41. cxd7 a2 42. d8=Q a1=Q+ {[%cal Ra1e1,Rc2e3] with a perpetual
check.}) 32. Bd4 a4 $2 {the losing move - after this everything goes downhill
for Black.} (32... Ne7 33. Ra8 Nf5 34. Be5 h5 35. Rxa5 Rb2 36. Kg2 Rxc2+ 37.
Kh3 g6 $16) 33. Ra8 Rb1+ 34. Kg2 Rc1 35. Ra7+ Kg6 36. Rxg7+ Kh6 37. Ra7 Nxc3
38. Kh3 Nb5 (38... Rxc2 39. Rc7) 39. Rxa4 Rxc2 40. Be5 Kg6 41. Ra6 Kf7 42. Rb6
Rc5 43. Rb7+ Kg6 44. Rg7+ Kh6 45. Rg5 {[%cal Ge5g7]} 1-0

