{[%cal Rd7d5,Gc2c4] A typical position from Chapter 7 of the Rossolimo
database - Black is ambitious and intends to fight for the centre and has
opened the b-file for his rook. For this position there's a very simple rule
for White - go for a Maroczy Bind structure by playing c2-c4. I'll describe to
you a few scenarios: 1) Black plays d7-d5 - normally this shouldn't be
possible as you will have already managed to play c2-c4 before that. If Black
does go for the d7-d5 and lags behind in development, a general rule applies
that in White's best interest is to go for quick development and open the
position to start an immediate assault. In this scenario, White can discard the
Maroczy Bind structure and go for a quick development Nc3, followed by exd5,
Re1 and so on. Still, if later in the game after White has setup the Maroczy
Bind, Black does manage to play d7-d5, it is a very logical idea for White to
twice take on d5 and then use either/both d4 and d3 squares for outposts for
your pieces while the others target the lone d5 pawn. 2) Black's pawn
structure remains intact as he's developing his pieces first. Here White
should opt for a quick c2-c4-c5 by fixing the weak d7 pawn. This will
seriously limit Black's options in the future as most of the queenside will be
cut-off unless he will play d6 or d5. This is when White should happily
exchange the pawn on d6 and simply target the weak c6 pawn. 3) Black plays
d7-d6 and c6-c5 in order to activate his bishop from c8 to b7, also eyeing for
the d4-square, most notably for a black knight which might be rerouted
Ng6-e7-c6-d4, or for the bishop Be7-f6-d4. White should proceed with a
kingside attack f2-f4, followed by Rf3-h3 and Qh5. In some occasions, White can
also opt for the a2-a3 and b2-b4 breakthrough. The f2-f4 advance also might give
White positional ideas as e4-e5, thus seriously weakening the black c5 pawn. 4)
Black plays d7-d6 and e6-e5 to activate his bishop at c8 and yet again eyeing
for the d4 square. While on paper this looks great, most often it will leave a
black knight on g6 cut-off from the action and White can even more limit it by
playing g2-g3. In the meantime, White can think about conquering the d5 square
for his knight by playing b2-b4-b5 and forcing a pawn exchange.}  *

