1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 4. O-O Nge7 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Qb6 7. Nxc6 bxc6 {
both of the opponents know each other quite well - several months prior to this
game they competed in a World Cup match, and Fabiano was struggling to beat
the opponent's solid positions after 7...dxc6. In the end, he finally broke
through Slovenian GM's defences and most likely did his homework, so now Lenic
goes for the alternative.} 8. Bd3 {White chooses Maroczy Bind setup and the
queen can quickly jump to h5 to accelerate a kingside attack.} Ng6 9. c4 {
[%cal Gb1c3,Gc3a4,Gc4c5] White's plan is rather simple - after most of Black's
continuations proceed with Nc3-a4 and push c4-c5. After that Black will be
forced to play d7-d6 and the c-pawn will become very weak.} Be7 10. Nc3 O-O 11.
Na4 $1 Qc7 12. c5 d5 {there's hardly anything else Black can do - he has to go
for this push sooner or later.} 13. cxd6 Bxd6 {the critical position - Black
has the weak pawn but White's pieces are not yet coordinated.} 14. g3 $1 {
[%csl Gf4,Rg6,Gh4] an excellent positional move to take away many important
squares for the black pieces, most notably the knight on g6.} c5 15. Be3 Ne5
16. Be2 Bb7 {Black seems to have a good position with very active pieces and
even some threats but most likely Caruana after the lesson in the World Cup
was still within his home preparation.} 17. Rc1 $1 {White is ready to trade
his central e4 pawn for the weak c5 pawn, but doing so he secures himself a
pleasant little advantage in the upcoming endgame.} (17. f3 {would be too slow}
c4 18. Rc1 Qc6 {[%cal Rf7f5]}) (17. f4 Nd7 18. Qc2 Be7 19. Rfd1 Rfd8 20. Rac1 {
[%csl Re4] was also possible but Black could generate good enough counterplay
on the e4 pawn.}) 17... Bxe4 $6 {now Black will be suffering as he has to give
up one of the bishops} (17... Qc6 $1 {was more tricky as it would allow Black
to keep both bishops.} 18. Qc2 $1 Qxe4 (18... Rac8 19. Rfd1 $14) 19. Qxe4 Bxe4
{[%cal Re5f3]} 20. f4 $1 Nc6 21. Nxc5 Bd5 22. a3 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4] and despite
all the accuracy that Black has shown, he is still slightly worse.}) 18. Nxc5
Bc6 (18... Bxc5 {would be even worse} 19. Rxc5 Qb8 20. Bf4 Rd8 21. Qc1 Bd5 22.
Qe3 f6 23. b3 $16) 19. f4 Ng6 (19... Bxc5 20. Bxc5 Rfd8 21. Qc2 Ng6 22. b4 $14
{with a lot of practical problems for Black.}) 20. Ne4 $1 Rfd8 21. Qc2 {
White is very accurate and keeps growing his advantage.} Bxe4 22. Qxe4 Qa5 (
22... Qe7 23. Rc2 Rac8 24. Rfc1 Rxc2 25. Rxc2 {doesn't change the evaluation
of the position - White is much better.}) 23. f5 $16 Qe5 (23... exf5 24. Rxf5
Qb4 25. Bc4 $18) 24. Bf3 Qxb2 $4 {Lenic ends his suffering very quickly - he
could have put up much better resistance.} (24... Nh4 $1 25. Qxh4 Qxe3+ 26.
Kh1 Rac8 27. Rce1 Qc5 28. fxe6 {[%cal Gf3e4]} f5 $16 {Black has some practical
chances to save the game due to the opposite colour bishops but White's
advantage obviously can't be denied.}) 25. fxg6 hxg6 26. Qc2 Qa3 27. Qc3 1-0

