{[%cal Ga2a4,Gb2b3,Rf7f5,Ge4e5] This is a common pawn structure if Black in
the Rossolimo goes for one of the most solid approaches - 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.
Bb5 g6 4.Bxc6 dxc6 which we witnessed in the World Championship match between
Magnus Carlsen and Fabiano Caruana. Afterwards Black eventually goes e7-e5 and
White starts a kingside attack with f2-f4, thus exchanging the pawns. Here
White usually should concentrate on developing initiative on the f-file by
doubling the rooks and bring most of the pieces to the kingside. Sometimes a
manoeuvre e4-e5 might become possible if White has a knight on c3 so that it
can be rerouted to the kingside with Nc3-e4-f6. That is the reason why White
would want to have a bishop on g3 instead of e3 and potentially also Rae1 so
that the pawn on e5 is well protected. A good idea early on might be to play
a2-a4 to threaten to play a4-a5 - in that case make sure Black can't go pass
by b6-b5. Usually Black responds with a7-a5, thus blocking White's attempts at
the queenside. This manoeuvre is recommended if Black is thinking about long
castling. Maneuver b2-b3 would strengthen White's pawn structure at the
queenside so that he can concentrate on the kingside. Watch out for Black's
counterplay c5-c4 - this is yet another good reason to play b2-b3. Another
defensive measure from Black sometimes is f7-f5, trying to extinguish White's
attack and simplify the position. White's h, g and c-pawns usually stay where
they are and in most of the occasions shouldn't be advanced.}  *

