1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 Nf6 7. Nc3 Nd7 {
[%cal Re7e5,Rd7f8,Rf8e6] one of the main ideas in this variation - Black
postpones the castling and intends to play e7-e5, and reroute the knight to e6
where it controls f4 and d4 squares.} 8. Be3 e5 9. Qd2 {[%cal Ge3h6,Gf3h2,
Gf2f4] not only threatening Bh6 and preparing the eventual Nf3-h2 and f2-f4
move but also leaving long castling as an option.} h6 $6 {a dangerous choice -
Black doesn't want to allow the bishop trade but the practice shows that White
here scores much better than Black.} (9... Qe7 10. O-O Nf8 {should be a better
continuation for Black and it's not easy for White to claim an opening
advantage.}) 10. O-O Qe7 11. Nh2 Nf8 12. f4 exf4 13. Bxf4 Ne6 14. Bg3 $1 {
[%cal Ge4e5,Gc3e4] a modern idea to go for a quick kingside attack by the
means of e4-e5 and Ne4. Some time ago people used to take on f4 with the rook
and then retreat with it to f2. It all changed in 2005 when Alexei Shirov in a
blindfolded game against Loek van Wely first played this new idea and the
practice proves that Black here is struggling.} Nd4 ({The other alternative
actually is a forced line} 14... Qg5 15. Qe1 (15. Qf2 $4 Bd4) 15... Nd4 16. Qf2
$1 O-O 17. Bd6 Bxh3 18. Bf4 $1 {the point!} Qxg2+ 19. Qxg2 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 Nxc2
21. Rad1 $14 {Black has three pawns for a piece but there are too many pieces
on the board to call it a good trade. White certainly is better and can easily
press Black.}) 15. Rae1 O-O {either Baron was completely oblivious to what
White had in his mind or he believed that White's initiative is not a big deal.
} ({A more stubborn approach was going for a long castle although White is
better everywhere.} 15... Be6 16. e5 Nf5 17. Bf2 O-O-O) 16. e5 Bf5 {Black
tries to stop the Ne4 manoeuvre but doing so he no longer controls the g4
square. As it happens, White has not one but two knights that can jump to f6!}
(16... Nf5 17. Bf2 b6 18. Nf3 Be6 19. Ne4 $16 {[%cal Gg2g4,Ge4f6] would
probably end with the same result}) 17. Ne4 Bxe4 18. Rxe4 $16 {[%cal Gh2g4,
Gg4f6] Black has made supposedly only normal moves but clearly, something is
wrong with his position - White has free hands to attack the black king and
it's not clear how to protect him. This only proves that the whole line for
Black is just bad.} h5 $2 {You can't really blame Black for the error - the
position is already very unpleasant for him. Black stops the knight's jump to
g4 but at a too great cost - it even further weakens Black's king position and
White immediately starts the decisive assault.} (18... Nf5 19. Bf2 b6 20. Nf3 {
[%cal Gg2g4] White is clearly in the driver's seat and can slowly increase the
pressure but at least the black king in the given moment is safe.} (20. Ng4 $6
{wouldn't make much sense as the black knight on f5 takes care of everything
and White can't get rid of it as long as his own knight stands on g4.})) 19.
Bh4 Qe6 20. g4 $1 {And that's it, game over - thanks to the weakness on h5,
Black has no chances to survive this attack.} Qxa2 {Black goes down no matter
what so grabbing a few pawns is the best practical chance. Maybe White won't
find the right continuation in the attack? Against somebody else, it might have
worked but for the brilliant attacker Emil Sutovsky this is a piece of cake.} (
20... Bxe5 21. Bf6 {with huge material gains for White} Bxh2+ 22. Kh1 $1 {
[%cal Gd2h6,Gh6h8]}) 21. gxh5 Qxb2 22. h6 $1 {the simplest.} Bh8 23. h7+ $1
Kxh7 24. Bf6 {[%cal Ge4h4,Gd2h6] Black will be checkmated shortly so this is
the right time to resign.} 1-0

