{[%cal Ra7a5,Gd1a1,Ga1e5,Ga1a7,Rc5c4] This is one of the most important
positions of the Rossolimo variation. Usually, it arises if Black goes for the
solid approach after 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 g6 4.Bxc6 dxc6 and then for a
quick e7-e5, followed by Nf6. As explained in the database, this is the moment
when White should be thinking about a2-a3 and b2-b4 breakthrough because the
main motif of f2-f4 might not be so effective because of the black knight from f6
can immediately jump to h5, making the push more difficult to achieve. Since
the black bishop on g7 is blocked by his own pawn, now the b2-b4 idea is
possible. With the a2-a3 and b2-b4 push White wants to accomplish one of the
ideas: 1) Black takes on b4, and White responds with axb4 - then the rook on
a1 becomes very active and can target the a7 pawn. Here White usually can try
to double heavy pieces on the a-file by the means of Ra3 or even Ra5, followed
by Qa1, pressuring both a7 and e5 pawns. Sometimes the queen can go to b1-b2,
freeing the a1 square for the other rook. If Black is passive after the pawn
exchange White can either go for d3-d4, gaining a pawn majority at the
kingside and try to oppress Black's pawn majority at the queenside, or execute
a typical idea c2-c4-c5, followed by Nd2-c4. If Black would meet the c2-c4
with c6-c5, this would seriously weaken the d5 square and White can reroute
there his knight. An important note - a standard defensive measure for Black
after the pawn exchange on b4 is to push a7-a5 by liquidating White's pressure
at the queenside. This means that either White should be ready or it or before
executing the b2-be break to try to provoke Black to play b7-b6 first (Be3
attacks the pawn), so that after the b-pawn exchange the a7-a5 manoeuvre just
ruins Black's pawn structure. 2) Black can try to ignore the pawn exchange so
White can remind him of the consequences by a typical knight manoeuvre Nbd2-b3
or c4. Very often it's a principled approach for White to take the pawn on c5
and, if necessary, defend it with Be3. If Black plays an immediate Nf6-d7 to
regain the captured pawn, very often White can play a3-a4 so that Nxc5 is met
by Ba3 with a pin to the rook on f8, and after that maybe even Nbd2-b3. It is
important for White not to miss that sometimes Black can meet the b2-b4 push
with c5-c4 - this is why a white knight on d2 is situated perfectly.}  *

