1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 e5 {if Black goes
for an early e7-e5 push, this allows White to start a quick offensive at the
queenside. The standard plan for White to go for f2-f4 here won't work because
the black knight will make it to h5 on time.} 7. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4]} (7. Nc3 Qe7
8. O-O Nf6 9. Nh2 Nh5 $11) 7... Ne7 $6 {although the quickest way to finish
the development, the knight is clearly misplaced on e7.} ({usually Black goes
for} 7... Qe7 {[%cal Rg8f6,Rf6d7] and reroutes the knight to d7 where it
controls the c5 and e5 pawns that White might be willing to pressure.}) ({
a standard approach to stop the b2-b4 is} 7... a5 8. Be3 Qe7 9. Nbd2 Nf6 10.
Nc4 Nd7 {and now White has to either make b2-b4 happen real soon or at least
he can fix the position of the knight on c4 by playing a3-a4.} 11. a4 O-O 12.
O-O b6 13. b3 Ba6 14. Nfd2 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 8. b4 (8. Be3 b6 9. b4 {[%cal Re7d5,
Re5e4,Rg7a1] also looks interesting as White has forced Black to include b7-b6
which considerably weakens the a7 pawn but this allows Black to execute a
crazy idea Nd5!?}) 8... cxb4 9. axb4 $14 {strategically wise this is a great
position for White - it would be even better if White could have provoked
Black to play b7-b6.} O-O 10. O-O h6 {[%cal Rg6g5,Re7g6] Since Black awkwardly
developed his knight on e7, he has to generate some counterplay at the
kingside after g6-g5 and Ng6 otherwise he has no game plan.} 11. Bb2 Qc7 12.
Nbd2 g5 13. Ra3 $1 {[%cal Gd1a1,Ga1e5,Ga1a7] a standard idea in this setup -
White's queen might go to a1 to pressure both a7 and e5 pawns at the same time!
} a6 14. Nc4 {since Black has already committed himself to a6, there's no need
to put the queen on a1 for the time being. White eyes for another target.} Ng6
15. Ne3 {[%csl Rf5]} f5 $6 {a too drastic decision - this creates even more
weaknesses in Black's camp. Despite the fact that White has managed to execute
the main idea in this line, Black is still very solid.} (15... Nf4 16. Re1 Re8
17. Bc3 f6 18. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2f1,Gf1g3,Gg3f5] and White will slowly reroute his
knight to f5 - Black is slightly worse but not by a big margin.}) 16. exf5 Bxf5
17. Nxf5 Rxf5 18. Nd2 {[%csl Ge4] Black has taken care of the f5 outpost but
created another on e4.} Nf4 19. Ne4 Re8 $16 {[%csl Ge4,Rg7] Karjakin's
advantage is obvious - he has a better pawn structure and a safer king. Still,
it's not easy to convert it as White will need to open the position sooner or
later. White needs to get rid of the knight from f4 and prepare a pawn
breakthrough - the only one possibility here is c2-c4 and b4-b5.} 20. Bc1 Rf7 21.
Rb3 {preparing the breakthrough in a near future} Re6 22. g3 $1 Nd5 23. c4 {
two birds with one shot - White pushes further away from the only active piece that
Black has got and is ready for b4-b5.} Ne7 {[%cal Re7f5,Rf5d4]} 24. b5 cxb5 25.
cxb5 {mission accomplished - White is ready to invade Black's back rank and
bother either the weakened king or the weaknesses.} Nf5 26. Rc3 $6 {until this
moment Sergey Karjakin played beautiful positional chess, gradually
increasing the pressure. White had to take care of the d4 square and bring
into play his rook on f1.} (26. Bb2 $1 axb5 27. Rxb5 Rb6 28. Qb3 Rxb5 29. Qxb5
$16 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gf1a1,Ga1a8,Ga1a5] and White's pieces should penetrate
Black's ranks really quick. If possible, White would love to swap the bishop
for the knight which would ensure an eternal pressure. In the example,} Nd4 30.
Bxd4 exd4 31. Rb1 Qd7 32. Qxd7 Rxd7 33. Rb6 {[%csl Rb7,Ge4,Rg7][%cal Gg1g2,
Gf2f4,Gf4f5]}) 26... Qd8 27. bxa6 Rxa6 28. Kg2 Rc6 $6 {Black willingly
eliminates his only possibility for a counterplay - the passed pawn.} (28...
Bf8 {[%cal Rb7b5,Rf5d4,Rf7b7] and Black should think about moving his b-pawn
forward, with the help of Nd4. White is still better though.}) 29. Rxc6 bxc6
30. Qc2 Qd5 31. Rd1 $6 {too slow - I just don't understand why White
stubbornly doesn't want to activate his rook on either a1 or c1! The final
moves of the game are not of the best quality so I can only assume that both
players were in time trouble.} Ra7 32. Bb2 Ra2 {if the rooks will come off
the board, the position will be very drawish. Naturally White is not in a
hurry for a trade.} 33. Rb1 Nd4 $6 (33... Nd6 {there was no better moment to
eliminate the annoying knight on e4!}) 34. Qd1 Nb5 35. Kh2 Qf7 36. Qg4 $6 {
the idea to switch to a counter-attack is a good decision, especially in
time trouble but the implementation could have been better.} (36. Kg1 {was an
important intermezzo to protect the f2 pawn.}) 36... Ra8 (36... Nd6 $1 {
[%cal Rf7f2,Ra2b2]} 37. Kg2 Nxe4 38. dxe4 Kh7 {and because of the active black
rook on a2 White has no time to target Black's weaknesses. The position is
just equal.} 39. Qf5+ Qxf5 40. exf5 e4 $1 $11) 37. h4 {Black forfeited on time
but his position yet again is rather unpleasant.} 1-0

