{[%cal Rd7d6,Gd4h4,Gc1h6,Gb1c3,Gc3e4] This type of position can be reached
from two different variations: either 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 g6 4.Bxc6 bxc6 5.
0-0 Bg7 6.Re1 Nf6 7.e5 Nd5 8.c4 Nc7 9.d4 cxd4 10.Qxd4 or following the new
main line from the Rossolimo database update (Chapter 10): 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.
Bb5 g6 4.Bxc6 bxc6 5.d4 cxd4 6.Qxd4 Nf6 7.e5 and later c2-c4. White typically
starts an assault at the kingside with Qd4-h4, followed by Bh6 threat and
Nc3-e4-g5. Thus Black can't be passive and ignore what's going on so he goes
for one of the following ideas: 1) In order to stop the standard manoeuvre
Bc1-h6, Black very often plays either h7-h6 or h7-h5. By doing so he leaves
himself the only breakthrough option d7-d6 so White should be ready for it. If
the black pawn is on h6, Black can't castle so g6-g5 with an idea to castle
might be possible but that will jump under the h2-h4 threat at some point. If
the pawn is on h5, is will forever weaken the g5 square, most notably for the
white bishop. 2) If Black plays d7-d6, White can either take on d6 or ignore
it for the time being and offer to take on e5 for Black himself. If White
takes on d6, Black usually takes it with the queen and then tries to grab the
centre by the means of e7-e5, f7-f5 and maybe even e5-e4, combined with the
power of the two bishops. Thus White can't afford to be slow and should
generate a clear plan until then. If Black takes on d6 with a pawn, he is just
worse and White can easily organize pressure on the weak d6 pawn and an
outpost in the centre. 3) If Black plays d7-d5, White has two options - either
take on d6 or go for cxd5 and create an outpost on d4 for one of the light
pieces which should help to boost White's attack at the kingside. 4) Usually,
it's a not so great idea for Black to play f7-f6 although it opens the rook on
f8 (assuming Black has made a short castle) and the bishop on g7. Then White
can simply capture on f6 and Black has to take it with a piece, otherwise, he
will get a worse version of the pawn structure, mentioned in the 2nd point.
Then White can position both rooks on the d and e-files, targeting the weak
pawns, combined together with a typical c4-c5 push, creating a lot of
weaknesses in Black's camp. 5) If Black goes for an immediate c6-c5 to open
the bishop from c8-b7, then White should block it with a manoeuvre Nc3-d5. The
idea of c6-c5 is more common if Black plays d7-d6 first, then takes with the
queen, and finally plays c6-c5 and Bb7. No matter what Black does, he will
always have a worse pawn structure. So in his best interest it is to
compensate it with a very active play and a two bishop advantage, so White
would be very happy to exchange the dark-squared bishops for a long-lasting
positional pressure. If Black doesn't allow it to trade via h6, White can do
it via d2-c3.}  *

