1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 bxc6 {the most ambitious continuation -
Black goes for a complex strategic battle with plans to fight for a strong
pawn centre and use the open b-file for the rook.} 5. O-O Bg7 6. Re1 Nf6 {
not the most popular continuation but a perfectly playable choice.} (6... Nh6
7. c3 O-O 8. h3 f5 9. e5 Nf7 10. d3 {is more popular at the top level.}) 7. e5
Nd5 8. c4 {White goes for the most reasonable game plan available in this
position - to push back the black knight and transfer the queen to h4, where
it will be ideally positioned for a potential kingside attack, and as well as
for the Bh6 manoeuvre which favours White.} Nc7 9. d4 (9. b3 $5 {is an
interesting alternative, avoiding to exchange the pawns on d4 and trying to
exploit Black's doubled pawns.} Ne6 10. Bb2 d6 11. Nc3 Nd4 $1 12. exd6 Qxd6 13.
Ne4 Qc7 14. Nxd4 cxd4 15. Ba3 O-O 16. d3 $11 {1/2-1/2 (57) Amin,B (2680)-Erdos,
V (2628) Tbilisi 2017}) 9... cxd4 10. Qxd4 Ne6 11. Qh4 {[%cal Gc1h6,Gb1c3,
Ga1d1] White has an easy plan - exchange the dark-squared bishops and place
both rooks on the d and e-files, combined together with Nc3-e4-g5 threats.
Black has to do something real quick to not to land into trouble.} d6 $1 {
Very accurate - Black frees the bishop on g7. The sooner he can do it, the
better.} (11... f6 $6 {is not so great because of} 12. Bh6 {[%cal Gb1c3,Ga1d1]
and White's lasting pressure at the d and e-files will be quite unpleasant for
Black.}) (11... O-O $6 {is just too slow} 12. Bh6 f6 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Nc3 $16)
12. exd6 (12. Bh6 $6 {White would love to exchange the bishops but at the
moment it just doesn't work.} Bxe5 13. Nxe5 dxe5 {[%cal Rd8d1,Ge1e5] and White
can't take the pawn because of the back rank weakness.}) 12... Qxd6 13. Nc3 h5 {
The only reason why Black would be willing to go to this variation is to have
the two bishop advantage and dream for a strong pawn centre. Once it's gone,
White's advantage becomes obvious as Black's pawn structure is crippled and
also the pieces are not optimally placed.} ({it is also possible to go for} 
13... Bf6 {but then Black will be struggling in a slightly unpleasant endgame
albeit most likely holdable.} 14. Ne4 Bxh4 15. Nxd6+ exd6 16. Nxh4 f6 {
numerous weaknesses in Black's camp promise White an easy game to play for a
win with no risk involved.}) (13... O-O 14. Bh6 f6 15. Rad1 Qc7 16. Bxg7 Nxg7
17. Qd4 e5 18. Qd6 $14 {and White is clearly pressing.}) 14. Bd2 $1 {[%cal
Gc3e4,Gd2c3] if White can't force Black to exchange the bishop via h6, there
are other options as well!} O-O 15. Ne4 Qc7 16. Bc3 f6 $5 {[%cal Re6f4,Re7e5,
Rg6g5] not mandatory but a reasonable decision - Black's keeps alive the dream
of the two bishop advantage. Black would love to play Nf4 and start marching
forward with the central pawns. White must act quick and precise.} 17. Rad1 Qf4
$2 {a bad mistake which could have cost Black dearly.} (17... Nf4 18. Nd4 Rd8
$1 {and the game remains complex with chances for both sides} (18... e5 $6 19.
Ne2 g5 20. Qg3 Bg4 21. f3 Nxe2+ 22. Rxe2 Be6 23. h4 $1 $14 {and despite the
fact that Black has kept the two bishop advantage and has a pawn centre, his
king is in danger.})) 18. Bb4 {good but White had an even better continuation
at his disposal.} (18. Qxf4 $1 Nxf4 19. Nd4 {[%csl Rc6] and Black loses the c6
pawn with no compensation whatsoever and White will have an easy plan of
marching forward with the pawns at the queenside.} Bb7 20. Nc5 {[%cal Ge1e7]
is curtains}) 18... Qxh4 $6 {mistakes usually come in pairs - now Black is
just lost. He had to accept the fact that two tempos are gone and retreat back
with the queen.} (18... Qc7 19. Nc5 Nxc5 20. Bxc5 Re8 21. Qe4 Bf5 22. Qe2 e5
23. Nh4 $16 {and Black is still suffering but at least it's not a forced loss.}
) 19. Nxh4 Kf7 20. Bxe7 $1 {a pretty little combination which should have led
White to an easy win.} Kxe7 21. Nxg6+ Kf7 22. Nxf8 Bxf8 23. Nd6+ $1 {a good
way to simplify the position} Bxd6 24. Rxd6 c5 $16 {the dust has settled,
White has a material advantage and should be technically winning. He has two
options at his disposal - either trade the rooks and attack the weak a7 pawn,
combined together with organizing passed pawns on both flanks, or create a
two pawn advantage in one of the flanks. The latter seems to be the easiest to
achieve.} 25. Rd5 Kg6 26. Rd6 $6 {a strange decision} (26. h4 $1 Rb8 27. Re3
Rxb2 28. Rg3+ Kh6 29. Rf5 {and White should eventually win as the pawns will
start marching forward.}) 26... Rb8 $1 {Black immediately exploits White's
inaccuracy and finds the best practical chance - after all, rook endgames have
a high tendency to be drawish!} 27. b3 {Of course, White doesn't want to find
out if the particular rook endgame will lead to a draw and keeps more pieces
on the board.} Kf7 $2 ({a more stubborn defense was} 27... Rb6 28. Rxb6 axb6
$14 {but now White can switch to the alternate plan of creating passed pawns
at both flanks and the b6 pawn at some moment might fall as well. Nevertheless,
this was the best try for Black.}) 28. f3 $2 {White misses another opportunity
to win the game.} (28. Rd5 Kg6 29. f4 $1 {[%cal Gf4f5,Gd5c5]} f5 (29... Nxf4
30. Rd8 $1 {[%cal Ge1e8] and Black loses a whole piece}) 30. Ree5 h4 31. Rd6
Kf6 32. Rc6 {and at least one more black pawn will fall, in with that the
entire game.}) 28... a5 $1 {the last chance for Black - activate the rook!} 29.
Rd5 a4 30. Rxh5 {finally White has managed to create two passed pawns in one
flank but now Black is very active.} axb3 31. axb3 Rxb3 32. Rh7+ Kg6 {probably
both players at this point were in time trouble thus a lot of mistakes a
bound to happen.} 33. Re7 $2 (33. Rh8 {White had to start marching forward
with the pawns - the sooner, the better!} Bd7 34. h4 Rc3 35. h5+ Kg7 36. Ra8
Kh6 37. Ra7 Bc8 38. Rf7 Kxh5 39. Rxf6 Kg5 40. Rexe6 Bxe6 41. Rxe6 Rxc4 42. Kf2
{still should be winning for White}) 33... Nf4 $11 34. R7e4 Nd3 35. R4e3 $2 Ba6
36. Rd1 Bxc4 $17 37. h4 Bb5 38. g4 c4 39. h5+ Kg5 40. Kh2 Rb2+ 41. Kg3 Nf4 42.
Rg1 {and just like that - White is completely lost now!} Ne2+ 43. Rxe2 Rxe2 44.
Rb1 Bc6 45. Rb6 Re6 46. f4+ Kh6 47. Kh4 c3 48. Rb3 c2 49. Rc3 Be4 $4 {this
normal looking move actually allows White to escape with a draw!} (49... Ba4
50. Rc7 Re4 $1 51. Kg3 Re1 {and Black wins}) 50. Rc7 $1 {[%cal Gg4g5] and
Black has to give up the c-pawn not to get mated with g5+! The limited
material will lead to a draw so both of the opponents decided it's enough.}
1/2-1/2

