{[%cal Rf6f5,Rd7d6,Rc6c5,Gc4c5,Gb2b5] This uncommon pawn structure can be
reached if we follow the line 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 g6 4.Bxc6 bxc6 5.d4 cxd4
6.Qxd4 f6 and later c2-c4. Black probably will go for this position to get a
complex game and is ready for the time being to imprison his bishop on g7 and
make a breakthrough f6-f5 later. The black knight usually is developed Nh6-f7.
Pretty much no matter what Black does, White has the same plan - go for c4-c5
and pressure Black on the d-file, and potentially could increase the pressure
with b2-b4-b5. Here are several scenarios: 1) Black goes for an early f6-f5 -
White should take on f5 and position both rooks on the d and e-file and try to
exchange the dark-squared bishop via d4 or c3.2) If Black plays d7-d6, it can
be a signal that Black is preparing f6-f5, c6-c5 or even e7-e5, followed by
f7-f5. Either way, White should meet it with a prepared c4-c5 which might be
even a temporary pawn sacrifice. If Black plays d7-d6 and c6-c5, then he's
going to have a hard time to get rid of the white knight on d5 as e7-e6 will
seriously weaken the d6 pawn. White can also proceed with the manoeuvre Nf3-h4
and f2-f4-f5 to block the bishop on g7 forever. 3) If Black plays e7-e5 with
an idea to go for f6-f5 and leave the pawn on d7, White should go for c4-c5
and b2-b4-b5. Black's attack at the kingside can't be dangerous if the whole
queenside can't join it.}  *

