1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 bxc6 5. d4 $5 {a very interesting fresh
idea which I just analyzed for the Rossolimo database as the new alternate
main line for White!} cxd4 (5... Bg7 6. dxc5 Qa5+ 7. Nbd2 {is another
possibility - the position holds more venom than it actually looks from the
first sight.}) 6. Qxd4 f6 $5 {[%cal Rg8h6,Rh6f7,Rf8g7,Re8g8] with very
aggressive intentions! Black is seeking for a complicated game and voluntarily
imprisoning the bishop on g7 is just temporary.} (6... Nf6 7. e5 Nd5 8. O-O Bg7
9. Qh4 $1 {[%cal Gc2c4,Gb1c3,Gc1h6] leads to a known typical position from
another popular Rossolimo line but with a different order of the moves 1.e4 c5
2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 g6 4.Bxc6 bxc6 5.0-0 Bg7 6.Re1 Nf6 7.e5 Nd5 8.c4 Nc7 9.d4 cxd4
10.Qxd4. However, if we compare both positions, there is one major thing why
this particular position should better for White - he has managed to save
tempo for Re1! Thus the Bh6 threat comes one move earlier.}) 7. O-O Bg7 {
a slight inaccuracy - this gives White a yet another option which he actually
used in the game.} (7... Nh6 {[%cal Rh6f7,Rf8g7] This would have been a more
precise move order - comparing to what happened in the game, now White
probably wouldn't want to take on h6.}) 8. c4 $1 {The Maroczy Bind setup
appears to be a universal cure for all Sicilian problems!} Nh6 9. Bxh6 $5 {
it's extremely tempting to punish Black for the supposed loss of the tempo but
it was not really required.} (9. Rd1 Nf7 10. c5 O-O 11. Nc3 {[%cal Gd1d7,Gb2b5,
Gd4c4,Re7e5,Rf6f5] White is pressing on the d-file and will march forward at
the queenside to create more targets. The position is very complex.}) 9... Bxh6
10. Rd1 O-O 11. c5 {[%csl Rd7]} Rb8 12. b3 $6 {a strange loss of time - nobody
is really targeting the b-pawn at the moment as it's well defended by the
queen.} (12. Qc3 Qc7 13. Nbd2 d6 14. cxd6 Qxd6 15. b3 {[%csl Rc6] and White is
slightly pushing as the black bishops are not yet working well enough.}) 12...
Kh8 $2 {Black can't afford to be so slow - he needs to open the position or at
least bring the queenside pieces into the game real quick otherwise White's
pressure on the d-file will become overwhelming. As it happens, this was the
best moment to do it.} (12... Ba6 $1 13. Qxd7 (13. Nbd2 d5 14. cxd6 Qxd6 $11) (
13. Qb2 f5 14. e5 Bc4 $1 15. Nc3 Be6 $13) (13. Nc3 $6 Qa5 {doesn't look good
for White}) 13... Qxd7 14. Rxd7 Rbd8 15. Rxd8 Rxd8 {[%cal Rh6c1,Ra6f1,Rd8d1]
and the activity of the rook, combined with the power of the two bishops
should give Black a more than enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn.})
13. Na3 $1 {[%cal Ga3c4] a great positional move - White takes care of any
future pawn breakthroughs in the centre that Black might be dreaming about.}
Qa5 14. Nc4 Qb4 15. Ne1 $1 {[%cal Ge1d3,Ge1c2] it becomes quite apparent that
Black will no longer be able to either make a successful breakthrough in the
centre or bring the queenside pieces to life. White continues to increase
pressure.} Qb7 16. Rd3 Qc7 17. Rad1 $16 Bg7 {Black lacks an active game plan
and can only watch how White slowly tortures him to death.} 18. Qe3 Rd8 19. Qd2
$6 {slightly careless - Firouzja should have been more alert that Black is
desperately seeking for ways to activate his pieces.} (19. Nc2 $1 Ba6 20. N2a3
{not allowing any activity for Black.}) 19... Rb5 $2 (19... Ba6 $1 20. Rxd7
Rxd7 21. Qxd7 Qxd7 22. Rxd7 Bxc4 23. bxc4 Bf8 $14 {[%cal Re7e5,Rf8c5,Rb8b4]
and Black is still alive.}) 20. b4 Rb8 21. Na5 $1 {the end is near - Black is
completely helpless.} Bf8 22. a3 Kg7 23. Nf3 {[%csl Ga5,Rc8,Gf3,Rf8][%cal
Gd2c3,Ge4e5] just watch how those bishops look completely powerless compared
to the knights!} d6 $6 {desperation at least to imitate some activity but it
immediately ends the game. Black was too passive the whole game and will be
buried together with his two bishops.} 24. Nd4 Re8 (24... dxc5 25. Ne6+ Bxe6
26. Rxd8 Rb5 {might had been more stubborn but it shouldn't change the outcome
of the game.}) 25. Ndxc6 Ra8 26. Rc1 $1 {[%csl Re8] Firouzja doesn't give his
opponent even the slightest hope for an activity.} dxc5 27. Rxc5 e5 28. Rc1 Qb6
29. Nc4 $1 Qa6 (29... Qxc6 30. Nd6 Qd7 31. Nxe8+ Qxe8 32. Rd8 Qe6 33. Rc7+ Be7
34. Re8 {would had been a different ending of the game.}) 30. N6a5 Re6 31. a4
Re8 32. Nd6 {[%cal Gc1c6] a very instructive game how two knights can
overpower two bishops and why being passive is never a good choice!} 1-0

